n\n<ref name=\"NYT-20200326\">{{cite news |last=McNeil, Jr. |first=Donald G. |title=The U.S. Now Leads the World in Confirmed Coronavirus Cases\u2014Following a series of missteps, the nation is now the epicenter of the pandemic. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/26/health/usa-coronavirus-cases.html |date=26 March 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n<!--==Sources attribution==-->* {{Free-content attribution |title=290 million students out of school due to COVID-19: UNESCO releases first global numbers and mobilizes response |publisher=UNESCO |documentURL= https://en.unesco.org/news/290-million-students-out-school-due-covid-19-unesco-releases-first-global-numbers-and-mobilizes |licence statement URL= https://en.unesco.org/news/290-million-students-out-school-due-covid-19-unesco-releases-first-global-numbers-and-mobilizes |licence=CC BY-SA 3.0 IGO|howto=no }}\n*{{Free-content attribution |title=Coronavirus impacts education |publisher=UNESCO |documentURL= https://en.unesco.org/themes/education-emergencies/coronavirus-school-closures |licence statement URL= https://en.unesco.org/themes/education-emergencies/coronavirus-school-closures |licence=CC BY-SA 3.0 IGO|howto=no }}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Sister project links|voy=2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic|c=category:COVID-19 pandemic|d=Q81068910|q=no|b=no|v=no|s=Category:COVID-19|m=no|mw=no|wikt=COVID-19|species=Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|n=Category:COVID-19}}\n{{Scholia}}\n\n===Government health agencies===\n\n* [https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019 COVID-19] ([http://www.who.int/news-room/q-a-detail/q-a-coronaviruses Questions & Answers], [https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLbpi6ZahtOH5PLTT1yfXxcxDsNM40N1uG Instructional Videos]) by the [[World Health Organization]]\n* [https://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en/novel-coronavirus-china COVID-19] ([http://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en/novel-coronavirus-china/questions-answers Q&A]) by the [[European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control]]\n* [http://en.nhc.gov.cn/antivirusfight.html COVID-19] by the [[China National Health Commission]]\n* [https://www.moh.gov.sg/covid-19 COVID-19] ([http://www.moh.gov.sg/covid-19/faqs Q&A]) by the [[Singapore Ministry of Health]]\n* [https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/index.html COVID-19] ([https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/about/index.html Q&A]) by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|U.S. Centers for Disease Control]]\n* [https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/emres/2019_ncov.html Coronavirus Disease 2019] ([https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/docs/2018-130/pdfs/2018-130.pdf?id=10.26616/NIOSHPUB2018130 Q&A]) by the [[National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health]]\n\n===Directories===\n\n* [https://curlie.org/Health/Conditions_and_Diseases/Respiratory_Disorders/COVID-19/ COVID-19 Directory on Curlie]\n* [https://openmd.com/directory/covid-19 COVID-19 Resource Directory on OpenMD]\n\n===Data and maps===\n\n* [https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/situation-reports/ Coronavirus disease (COVID-2019) situation reports] and [https://experience.arcgis.com/experience/685d0ace521648f8a5beeeee1b9125cd map] by the [[World Health Organization]]\n* [https://www.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6 Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases] and [https://github.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19 historical data] created by [[Lauren Gardner (scientist)|Lauren Gardner]] at [[Johns Hopkins University]]\n* [http://unwfp.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/42b8837bb25049b9b1f69a9555d55808 World Travel Restrictions] based on [[World Food Programme|WFP]] data\n* [https://covid.observer Coronavirus Observer] based on [[Johns Hopkins University]] data\n\n===Medical journals===\n\n* [https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/pages/coronavirus-alert Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19)] by [[JAMA (journal)|JAMA]]\n* [https://www.bmj.com/coronavirus Coronavirus: News and Resources] by [[BMJ (company)|BMJ Publishing Group]]\n* [https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center Novel Coronavirus Information Center] by [[Elsevier]]\n* [https://www.thelancet.com/coronavirus COVID-19 Resource Centre] by [[The Lancet]]\n* [https://www.springernature.com/gp/researchers/campaigns/coronavirus SARS-CoV-2 and COVID-19] by [[Nature (journal)|Nature]]\n* [https://www.nejm.org/coronavirus Coronavirus (Covid-19)] by [[New England Journal of Medicine]]\n* [https://novel-coronavirus.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/ Covid-19: Novel Coronavirus] by [[Wiley (publisher)|Wiley Publishing]]\n\n<!-- TO AVOID TECHNICAL ERRORS PLEASE DO NOT ADD MORE NAVBOXES HERE -->\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2019-20 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2010s disease outbreaks]]\n[[Category:2019 disasters in Asia]]\n[[Category:2019 disasters in China]]\n[[Category:2019 health disasters]]\n[[Category:2019 in international relations]]\n[[Category:2020 disasters in Asia]]\n[[Category:2020 health disasters]]\n[[Category:2020 in international relations]]\n[[Category:2020s disease outbreaks]]\n[[Category:21st-century epidemics]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Atypical pneumonias]]\n[[Category:Current events]]\n[[Category:December 2019 events in China]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in China]]\n[[Category:Health disasters in China]]\n[[Category:History of Wuhan]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in China]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in China]]\n[[Category:Occupational safety and health]]\n[[Category:Pandemics]]\n[[Category:Public Health Emergency of International Concern]]\n", "name_user": "Redthreadhx", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDiagrams:Fixed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic"}
{"title_page": "RCGS Resolute", "text_new": "{{short description|Cruise ship}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin|display title=''RCGS Resolute''}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image = RCGS Resolute.jpg\n| Ship caption = ''RCGS Resolute'' in [[Aberdeen]] in June 2019\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header = \n| Ship name = *''Society Adventurer'' (1991\u20131993)\n*''Hanseatic'' (1993\u20132018)\n*''RCGS Resolute'' (2018\u2013present)\n| Ship owner = * [[Discoverer Reederei]] (planned)<ref name=\"id\" />\n* Society Adventurer Shipping Company (1991\u20131993)<ref name=\"id\" /><ref group=\"note\">A fully-owned subsidiary of Rauma Yards</ref>\n* Bunnys Adventure & Cruise Shipping Co Ltd (1993\u2013present)<ref name=\"seaweb\" /><ref group=\"note\">A fully-owned subsidiary of [[Hanseatic Tours]] (later [[Hapag-Lloyd]])</ref>\n| Ship operator = * [[Hanseatic Tours]] (1993\u20131997)\n* [[Hapag-Lloyd Cruises]] (1997\u20132018)\n* [[One Ocean Expeditions]] (2018\u20132019)<ref name=\"seaweb\" />\n| Ship registry = * [[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]], {{BAH}} (1991\u20132018)\n* [[Madeira, Portugal|Madeira]], {{POR}} (2018\u2013present)<ref name=\"seaweb\" />\n| Ship route = \n| Ship ordered = 22 December 1989<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship builder = [[Finnish maritime cluster|Rauma Yards]] ([[Rauma, Finland|Rauma]], [[Finland]])<ref name=\"id\">{{cite|last1=Id|first1=Kalle|last2=Peter|first2=Bruce|title=Innovation and Specialisation \u2014 A History of Shipbuilding in Finland|publisher=Nautilus|year=2017|ISBN=9788790924683|page=}}</ref>\n| Ship original cost = US$75 million<ref name=\"id\" />\n| Ship yard number =306<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship laid down = 3 September 1990<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship launched = 5 January 1991<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship completed = 7 June 1991<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship christened = \n| Ship acquired = \n| Ship maiden voyage = 27 March 1993.<ref name=\"fof\" />\n| Ship in service = \n| Ship out of service = \n|Ship identification=* [[Maritime call sign|Call sign]]: CQAL6\n* {{IMO Number|9000168}}\n* {{MMSI|255806208}}<ref name=\"equasis\">{{csr|register=E|id=9000168|shipname=RCGS Resolute|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n* {{ship register|DNV|G99209}}<ref name=\"dnv\">{{csr|register=DNV|id=G99209|shipname=RCGS Resolute|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n| Ship status = In service\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header = \n| Header caption = <ref name=\"dnv\" /><ref name=\"Hapag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurolloyd.com/Hapag-Lloyd/HANSEATIC.pdf|title=MS ''Hanseatic'' Ship details|publisher=Hapag-Lloyd|accessdate=28 February 2009|format=PDF}}</ref>\n| Ship type = [[Cruise ship]]\n| Ship tonnage =* {{GT|8,445}}\n* {{NetT|2,573}}\n* {{DWT|1,177}}\n| Ship displacement = 5,892{{nbsp}}tonnes<ref name=\"seaweb\" />\n| Ship length = {{convert|124.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship beam = {{convert|18.00|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship height = \n| Ship draught = \n| Ship draft = {{convert|4.9|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship depth = {{convert|7|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship decks = 6\n| Ship deck clearance = \n| Ship ramps = \n| Ship ice class = [[DNV GL]] E4<ref name=\"ice class\" group=\"note\" />\n| Ship power = 2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}[[MaK]] 8M453C (2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}2,940{{nbsp}}kW)<ref name=\"seaweb\">{{csr|register=SEAWEB|id=9000168|shipname=RCGS Resolute|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n| Ship propulsion = Two shafts; [[controllable pitch propeller]]s\n| Ship speed = {{convert|16|kn}}\n| Ship range= {{convert|8600|nmi}}\n| Ship capacity = 184 passengers in 88 cabins and four suites\n| Ship crew = 125\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n|}\n\n'''''RCGS Resolute''''' is a [[star (classification)|five-star]] [[ice class|ice-strengthened]] expedition [[cruise ship]]. She was originally built as '''''Society Adventurer''''' in 1991, but after [[Discoverer Reederei]] was unable to take delivery of the vessel due to financial troubles, the completed ship was laid up at the shipyard for almost two years. She was acquired by [[Hanseatic Tours]] (later merged with [[Hapag-Lloyd]]) in 1993 and renamed '''''Hanseatic'''''. In 2018, she was chartered to [[One Ocean Expeditions]] and given her current name.\n\n== General characteristics ==\n\n''RCGS Resolute'' is {{convert|124.8|m|ftin}} [[length overall|long overall]] and {{convert|104.45|m|ftin}} [[length between perpendiculars|between perpendiculars]], has a beam of {{convert|18|m|ftin}} and draws {{convert|4.9|m|ftin}} of water with a [[Displacement (ship)|displacement]] of {{convert|5892|t|LT}}.<ref name=\"seaweb\" /> Her [[gross tonnage]] is 8,445; [[net tonnage]] 2,573; and [[deadweight tonnage]] 1,177 tonnes. The ship's hull and propulsion system are strengthened for navigation in ice-covered waters according to the [[DNV GL]] [[ice class]] E4.<ref name=\"dnv\" /><ref name=\"ice class\" group=\"note\">Equivalent to the highest [[Finnish-Swedish ice class]] for merchant ships, 1A Super</ref>\n\nBuilt to cater to the [[star (classification)|five-star]] luxury cruise market, interiors on the ''RCGS Resolute''{{'}}s six passenger-accessible decks were designed by the German architect [[Wilfried K\u00f6hnemann]].<ref name=\"id\" /> The vessel has 88 outside cabins and, above the bridge deck, four suites for a total of 184 passengers served by a crew of 125. Public spaces include a restaurant, multiple lounges, and a 78-seat theater. The ship carries 14 [[Zodiac inflatable boat]]s to take passengers ashore during expedition cruises.<ref name=\"Hapag\" /> \n\nThe ship's propulsion system consists of two [[straight-8 engine|eight-cylinder]] [[MaK]] 8M453C four-stroke medium-speed [[diesel engine]]s, each rated {{convert|2940|kW|hp}} at 600{{nbsp}}rpm, driving two [[controllable pitch propeller]]s. Onboard electrical power is generated by two {{convert|1160|kW|hp|adj=on}} [[straight-6 engine|six-cylinder]] MaK 6M332 auxiliary diesel generators and two {{convert|1040|kW|hp|adj=on}} main engine driven shaft generators. For maneuvering in ports, the ship has a {{convert|700|kW|hp|adj=on}} transverse [[bow thruster]].<ref name=\"seaweb\" /><ref name=\"dnv\" /> ''RCGS Resolute'' has a service speed of {{convert|16|kn}} and a cruising range of {{convert|8600|nmi}}.<ref name=\"Hapag\" />\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== ''Society Adventurer'' ===\n\nIn December 1989, the German cruise ship company [[Discoverer Reederei]] ordered a $75 million cruise ship from the Finnish shipbuilder [[Rauma Yards]] (formerly [[Rauma-Repola]]; later [[Finnyards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://meriteollisuus.teknologiateollisuus.fi/sites/meriteollisuus/files/inline-files/Meriteoll_historiikki_web.pdf|title=Kun rauta kelluu \u2014 V\u00e4l\u00e4hdyksi\u00e4 suomalaisen meriteollisuuden vuosisadasta|publisher=Meriteollisuus|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>) for its US-based subsidiary [[Society Expeditions]]. The ship, launched on 5 January 1991 as ''Society Adventurer'',<ref name=\"dnv\" /> was intended for adventure-style expedition cruises to remote destinations such as [[Antarctica]] and had, among other features, an ice-strengthened hull. However, Discoverer Reederei was unable to take delivery of the vessel in the following summer due to financial troubles and also had to cancel a [[sister ship]] that had already been contracted.<ref name=\"id\" /> As a result, the ownership of the vessel was transferred to Rauma Yards's newly-established Bahamas-registered subsidiary, Society Adventurer Shipping Company, on 7 June 1991.<ref name=\"dnv\" /> While on a lay-up at the yard, ''Society Adventurer'' was inspected by a number of parties interested in acquiring the vessel, among them the future [[president of the United States]] [[Donald Trump]].<ref name=\"id\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ls24.fi/uutiset/donald-trump-kavi-raumalla-laivakaupoilla-nayttelijavaimo-naytti-poseeraamisen-mallia|title=Donald Trump k\u00e4vi Raumalla laivakaupoilla - n\u00e4yttelij\u00e4vaimo n\u00e4ytti poseeraamisen mallia|work=L\u00e4nsi-Suomi|date=21 May 2016|accessdate=4 April 2020|language=fi}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.satakunnankansa.fi/satakunta/donald-trump-piipahti-1992-raumalla-laivakaupoilla-ja-tansseissa-13973980|title=Donald Trump piipahti 1992 Raumalla laivakaupoilla ja tansseissa|work=Satakunnan Kansa|date=9 November 2016|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Hanseatic'' ===\n[[File:Hanseatic 5.jpg|thumb|left|''Hanseatic'' sporting the classic [[Hamburg Atlantic Line]] livery in Nuuk, Greenland, in 2008.]]\n\nIn 1993, the ship was chartered and shortly afterwards purchased by the German expedition cruise operator [[Hanseatic Tours]].<ref name=\"id\" /> The company had been established two years earlier by [[Dirk Moldenhauer]], who had been the last captain of [[German Atlantic Line]]'s cruise ship [[TS Maxim Gorkiy|''Hanseatic'']] in 1973 and later acquired rights to the classic Hamburg Atlantic Line logo, livery and the name \"Hanseatic\".<ref name=\"simplonpc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.simplonpc.co.uk/HamburgAtlantik.html|title=Hamburg Atlantik Line/Deutsche Atlantik Line/Hanseatic Tours|accessdate=4 April 2020|author=Ian Boyle|work=Simplon Postcards}}</ref> ''Society Adventurer'' was renamed ''Hanseatic'' on 23 March 1993,<ref name=\"schwerdtner\">{{cite|title=German Luxury Ocean Liners: From Kaiser Wilhelm Der Grosse to Aidastella|last=Schwerdtner|first=Nils|publisher=Amberley Publishing|year=2013|}}</ref> becoming the fourth ship to bear the name, and the original blue-yellow-white Discoverer Reederei livery was replaced with the white hull and red decorative stripes.<ref name=\"id\" /> The vessel's maiden cruise from [[Hamburg]] to [[Sevilla]] began on 27 March 1993.<ref name=\"fof\">{{cite web|url=http://www.faktaomfartyg.se/society_adventurer_1991.htm|title=M/S Society Adventurer|work=Fakta om Fartyg|last=Asklander|first=Micke|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> When Hanseatic Tours was merged with [[Hapag-Lloyd Cruises]] in 1997, ''Hanseatic'' retained her original name as well as Hamburg Atlantic Line livery and funnel logo until rebranding in 2011.<ref name=\"schwerdtner\" /><ref name=\"seatrade\">{{cite web|url=https://www.seatrade-cruise.com/news-headlines/former-hanseatic-leaves-germany-after-long-career-hapag-lloyd|title=Former Hanseatic leaves Germany after long career with Hapag-Lloyd|work=Seatrade Cruise News|publisher=Informa Markets|date=8 October 2018|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n''Hanseatic'' remained in Hapag-Lloyd's fleet until 2018. Over the ship's 25-year career and a total of 667 cruises, she made 128 expeditions to Antarctica, two voyages to the [[Northern Sea Route]] (Northeast Passage), and transited the full length of the [[Northwest Passage]] 11 times.<ref name=\"seatrade\" /> The latter is a record number for passenger ships, exceeded only by the Russian [[icebreaker]] ''[[Kapitan Khlebnikov]]'' which is also used for expedition cruises.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spri.cam.ac.uk/resources/infosheets/northwestpassage.pdf|title=Transits of the Northwest Passage to the end of the 2019 navigation season|publisher=Scott Polar Research Institute|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> ''Hanseatic'' also holds the record for having been further north among passenger-carrying ships that are not icebreakers: on 26 August 2014, the vessel reached {{Coord|85|40.7|N|135|39.6|E|display=inline}}, {{convert|259|nmi}} from the [[North Pole]], due to unusually easy ice conditions in the Russian Arctic.<ref name=\"seatrade\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.travelpulse.com/news/cruise/expedition-ship-hanseatic-sets-new-record-for-passenger-ships.html|title=Expedition Ship Hanseatic Sets New Record for Passenger Ships|publisher=Travel Pulse|date=28 August 2014|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== ''RCGS Resolute'' ===\n\nIn June 2017, the Canada-based cruise ship operator [[One Ocean Expeditions]] announced that it would expand its fleet of expedition cruise ships with a long-term charter of the former ''Hanseatic''. The ship would be renamed ''RCGS Resolute'' after the 1850-built [[Royal Navy]] Arctic exploration vessel [[HMS Resolute|HMS ''Resolute'']] as well as the [[Inuit]] hamlet [[Resolute, Nunavut|Resolute]] in [[Nunavut]]. Furthermore, the ship would carry the initials of the [[Royal Canadian Geographic Society]] (RCGS) with whom One Ocean Expeditions had partnered.<ref name=\"oneocean_july2017\">{{cite web|url=https://discover.oneoceanexpeditions.com/rcgs-resolute/|title=One Ocean Expeditions Expands Fleet and Operations with New Vessel: RCGS RESOLUTE|publisher=One Ocean Expeditions|date=June 2017|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> After concluding her career with Hapag-Lloyd and a brief drydocking in Germany, the vessel headed to Canada in October 2018 under her new name and with new livery.<ref name=\"seatrade\" />\n\nIn 2019, the company's financial difficulties began to surface with the sudden withdrawal of the Russian research vessels ''[[Akademik Ioffe]]'' and ''[[Akademik Sergey Vavilov]]'' chartered from the [[Shirshov Institute of Oceanology]]. Although One Ocean Expeditions initially called the Russian owner's action a contract violation, it was later revealed that the company had failed to pay charter and fueling fees to the intermediate charterer Terragelida Ship Management which had then terminated the contract.<ref name=\"guardian_oct2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.pe.ca/business/regional-business/shipping-news-one-ocean-expeditions-sails-into-troubled-waters-370614/|title=SHIPPING NEWS: One Ocean Expeditions sails into troubled waters|date=31 October 2019|accessdate=5 April 2020|work=The Guardian|publisher=Saltwire Network}}</ref> This left One Ocean Expeditions with just one ship, ''RCGS Resolute''. In August, she was briefly arrested in [[Iqaluit]] over a C$100,000 payment dispute. While this issue was reportedly solved quickly,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.maritime-executive.com/article/cruise-ship-briefly-arrested-in-nunavut|title= Cruise Ship Briefly Arrested in Nunavut|publisher=The Maritime Executive|date=19 August 2019|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> another arrest over non-payment of services and crew wages followed in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]] next month. Finally, in October One Ocean Expeditions was forced to cancel an Antarctic cruise midway after the vessel could not be refueled due to the company's non-payment of outstanding debts. Shortly after the ship's 140 passengers disembarked, ''RCGS Resolute'' was detained in [[Buenos Aires]] over \"significant debt\".<ref name=\"guardian_oct2018\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/one-ocean-expeditions-ship-detained-1.5370649|title=Ship belonging to troubled B.C. expedition cruise company detained in Argentina|date=24 November 2019|publisher=CBC|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> The company entered administration in January 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cruisecritic.co.uk/news/4955/|title=One Ocean Expeditions Cruise Line Collapses|work=CruiseCritic|publisher=The Independent Traveler|date=13 January 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March 2020, ''RCGS Resolute'' left Buenos Aires after a total of US$3.6 million of outstanding debt was paid to fuel suppliers, ship agents and crew members.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thechronicleherald.ca/business/local-business/shipping-news-some-cruise-companies-scrap-schedule-others-continue-on-425502/|title=SHIPPING NEWS: Some cruise companies scrap schedule, others continue on|work=The Chronicle Herald|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Incidents ==\n\n=== 1996 grounding === \n\nOn 29 August 1996, ''Hanseatic'' ran aground in [[Simpson Strait]] in the Canadian Arctic. The vessel was eleven days into an eastbound transit along the Northwest Passage with 149 passengers and 110 crew, and had stopped at [[Gjoa Haven]] to let passengers ashore. Unknowingly to the crew, a green buoy marking a shallow shoal had not been removed after the previous navigating season and, over the winter months, had been moved to the northeast by about {{convert|200|m|yd}} by drifting ice. Shortly after departure, ''Hanseatic'' ran aground on the shoal at {{Coord|68|33.75|N|97|32.2|W|display=inline}}.<ref name=\"1996report\">{{cite web|url=https://bst-tsb.gc.ca/ENG/rapports-reports/marine/1996/m96h0016/M96H0016.pdf|title=Grounding of passenger vessel \"Hanseatic\" at Simpson Strait, Northwest Territories, 29 August 1996 (report number M96H0016)|publisher=Transport Safety Board of Canada|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nWith no danger of the vessel sinking, ''Hanseatic''{{'}}s passengers were allowed to explore the nearby islands using the ship's boats until the Russian icebreaker ''[[Kapitan Dranitsyn]]'' arrived to pick up the passengers on 5 September and continue the Northwest Passage expedition under charter by Hanseatic Tours. ''Hanseatic'' itself was successfully refloated on 8 September. While the ship's hull was damaged during the grounding, no oil spilled to the sea and there were no injuries among the passengers or the crew.<ref name=\"1996report\" />\n\n=== 1997 grounding ===\n\nOn 14 July 1997, ''Hanseatic'' was grounded on a sand bank in [[Murchisonfjorden]] in [[Svalbard]] with 145 passengers onboard.<ref>{{cite book|title=Navigation Safety and Risk Assessment Challenges in the High North|last1=Marchenko|first1=N.|last2=Borch|first2=O.J.|last3=Andreassen|first3=N.|last4=Kuznetsova|first4=S.Yu.|last5=Ingimundarson|first5=V.|last6=Jakobsen|first6=U.|work=Marine Navigation: Proceedings of the 12th International Conference on Marine Navigation and Safety of Sea Transportation (TransNav 2017), June 21-23, 2017, Gdynia, Poland|publisher=CRC Press|year=2017|page=345|isbn=978-13-5158-218-6}}</ref><ref name=\"penguins\">{{cite book|last=Wright|first=Christopher|title=Of Penguins and Polar Bears: A History of Cold Water Cruising|year=2020|publisher=The History Press|ISBN=978-07-5099-456-9}}</ref> No injuries nor damage to the ship was reported, and the passengers were again taken to explore nearby islands on ''Hanseatic''{{'}}s Zodiac boats while awaiting evacuation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/0e7c429f30ac4d87307fb0eea3de2220|title=Cruise ship stuck in Arctic after running aground|date=14 July 1997|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> By 17 July, the ship had been refloated and was heading towards [[Longyearbyen]] for inspection.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.travelweekly.com/Cruise-Travel/Hanseatic-Grounded-in-the-Arctic|title=Hanseatic Grounded in the Arctic|date=17 July 1997|publisher=Travel Weekly|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 2005 grounding ===\n\nIn August 2005, ''Hanseatic'' ran aground near the island of [[Lur\u00f8ya, Nordland|Lur\u00f8ya]] on the Norwegian coast, just south of the [[Arctic Circle]], with 160 passengers onboard. While the vessel was not in danger of sinking despite a {{convert|5|m|ft|adj=on}} hole in one of her [[ballast water]] tank, the passengers and part of the crew was nonetheless evacuated.<ref name=\"penguins\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ranablad.no/nyheter/cruiseskip-evakuert/s/1-93-1706219|title=Cruiseskip evakuert|language=no|work=Rana Blad|date=22 August 2005|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 2013 drydock fire ===\n\nOn 13 June 2013, a fire broke out in ''Hanseatic''{{'}}s engine room due to [[hot work]] in one of the ballast water tanks while the ship was in a [[drydock]] at the Bredo Shipyard in [[Bremerhaven]]. Due to delays in drydocking and additional repairs required by the fire, four cruises between 17 June and 1 August had to be cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/travel/news/2013/06/25/hapag-lloyd-hanseatic-fire/2455171/|title=Hapag-Lloyd cancels more cruises due to shipyard fire|work=USA Today|date=25 June 2013|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 2020 collision with Venezuelan patrol boat ''Naiguat\u00e1'' ===\n\nIn the early hours of 30 March 2020, ''RCGS Resolute'' was drifting in international waters, near [[Willemstad]], [[Curacao]], some {{convert|60|nmi}} off the country's northern coast, when the Venezuelan Coast Guard patrol boat {{ship|Venezuelan patrol boat|Naiguat\u00e1||2}}, also known by her hull number GC-23, approached her. The Venezuelan ship ordered the cruise ship to follow her to [[Puerto Moreno]] on [[Margarita Island]], located to the east, accusing her of violating the country's territorial waters. Gun shots were fired and, shortly thereafter, the navy vessel approached the starboard side at speed with an angle of 135\u00b0 and purposely collided with ''RCGS Resolute''. The {{convert|1,720|t|LT|adj=on}} navy vessel continued to ram the starboard bow in an apparent attempt to turn the heading of the {{convert|5,892|t|LT|adj=on}} cruise ship towards Venezuelan territorial waters. While ''RCGS Resolute'' sustained minor damage, not affecting vessel's seaworthiness, the navy vessel suffered severe damage while making contact with the [[ice class|ice-strengthened]] [[bulbous bow]] of the expedition cruise vessel ''RCGS Resolute'' and started to take water.<ref name=jpost20200403>{{cite news |url=https://www.jpost.com/International/Venezuelan-warship-shoots-rams-into-German-cruise-vessel-before-sinking-623422 |title=Venezuelan warship shoots, rams into German cruise vessel before sinking |work=[[Jerusalem Post]] |date=3 April 2020 |access-date=3 April 2020 }}</ref> Ultimately ''Naiguat\u00e1'' sank, leaving the 44 naval personnel to be rescued by another vessel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fleetmon.com/maritime-news/2020/29297/cruise-ship-sunk-venezuelan-navy-ship-and-fled-pro/?fbclid=|title=Cruise Ship Sunk Venezuelan Navy Ship after being Fired at and Rammed. Don\u2019t mess with Resolute.|last=Voytenko|first=Mikhail|date=1 April 2020|website=Fleet Mon|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>{{Better source|date=April 2020|reason=Non-NPOV}}<ref name=jpost20200403/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{commonscat|IMO 9000168}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Hapag-Lloyd Cruises}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:RCGS Resolute}}\n[[Category:Cruise ships]]\n[[Category:1991 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Rauma, Finland]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 2020]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Cruise ship}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin|display title=''RCGS Resolute''}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image = RCGS Resolute.jpg\n| Ship caption = ''RCGS Resolute'' in [[Aberdeen]] in June 2019\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header = \n| Ship name = *''Society Adventurer'' (1991\u20131993)\n*''Hanseatic'' (1993\u20132018)\n*''RCGS Resolute'' (2018\u2013present)\n| Ship owner = * [[Discoverer Reederei]] (planned)<ref name=\"id\" />\n* Society Adventurer Shipping Company (1991\u20131993)<ref name=\"id\" /><ref group=\"note\">A fully-owned subsidiary of Rauma Yards</ref>\n* Bunnys Adventure & Cruise Shipping Co Ltd (1993\u2013present)<ref name=\"seaweb\" /><ref group=\"note\">A fully-owned subsidiary of [[Hanseatic Tours]] (later [[Hapag-Lloyd]])</ref>\n| Ship operator = * [[Hanseatic Tours]] (1993\u20131997)\n* [[Hapag-Lloyd Cruises]] (1997\u20132018)\n* [[One Ocean Expeditions]] (2018\u20132019)<ref name=\"seaweb\" />\n| Ship registry = * [[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]], {{BAH}} (1991\u20132018)\n* [[Madeira, Portugal|Madeira]], {{POR}} (2018\u2013present)<ref name=\"seaweb\" />\n| Ship route = \n| Ship ordered = 22 December 1989<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship builder = [[Finnish maritime cluster|Rauma Yards]] ([[Rauma, Finland|Rauma]], [[Finland]])<ref name=\"id\">{{cite|last1=Id|first1=Kalle|last2=Peter|first2=Bruce|title=Innovation and Specialisation \u2014 A History of Shipbuilding in Finland|publisher=Nautilus|year=2017|ISBN=9788790924683|page=}}</ref>\n| Ship original cost = US$75 million<ref name=\"id\" />\n| Ship yard number =306<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship laid down = 3 September 1990<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship launched = 5 January 1991<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship completed = 7 June 1991<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship christened = \n| Ship acquired = \n| Ship maiden voyage = 27 March 1993.<ref name=\"fof\" />\n| Ship in service = \n| Ship out of service = \n|Ship identification=* [[Maritime call sign|Call sign]]: CQAL6\n* {{IMO Number|9000168}}\n* {{MMSI|255806208}}<ref name=\"equasis\">{{csr|register=E|id=9000168|shipname=RCGS Resolute|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n* {{ship register|DNV|G99209}}<ref name=\"dnv\">{{csr|register=DNV|id=G99209|shipname=RCGS Resolute|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n| Ship status = In service\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header = \n| Header caption = <ref name=\"dnv\" /><ref name=\"Hapag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurolloyd.com/Hapag-Lloyd/HANSEATIC.pdf|title=MS ''Hanseatic'' Ship details|publisher=Hapag-Lloyd|accessdate=28 February 2009|format=PDF}}</ref>\n| Ship type = [[Cruise ship]]\n| Ship tonnage =* {{GT|8,445}}\n* {{NetT|2,573}}\n* {{DWT|1,177}}\n| Ship displacement = 5,892{{nbsp}}tonnes<ref name=\"seaweb\" />\n| Ship length = {{convert|124.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship beam = {{convert|18.00|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship height = \n| Ship draught = \n| Ship draft = {{convert|4.9|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship depth = {{convert|7|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship decks = 6\n| Ship deck clearance = \n| Ship ramps = \n| Ship ice class = [[DNV GL]] E4<ref name=\"ice class\" group=\"note\" />\n| Ship power = 2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}[[MaK]] 8M453C (2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}2,940{{nbsp}}kW)<ref name=\"seaweb\">{{csr|register=SEAWEB|id=9000168|shipname=RCGS Resolute|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n| Ship propulsion = Two shafts; [[controllable pitch propeller]]s\n| Ship speed = {{convert|16|kn}}\n| Ship range= {{convert|8600|nmi}}\n| Ship capacity = 184 passengers in 88 cabins and four suites\n| Ship crew = 125\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n|}\n\n'''''RCGS Resolute''''' is a [[star (classification)|five-star]] [[ice class|ice-strengthened]] expedition [[cruise ship]]. She was originally built as '''''Society Adventurer''''' in 1991, but after [[Discoverer Reederei]] was unable to take delivery of the vessel due to financial troubles, the completed ship was laid up at the shipyard for almost two years. She was acquired by [[Hanseatic Tours]] (later merged with [[Hapag-Lloyd]]) in 1993 and renamed '''''Hanseatic'''''. In 2018, she was chartered to [[One Ocean Expeditions]] and given her current name.\n\n== General characteristics ==\n\n''RCGS Resolute'' is {{convert|124.8|m|ftin}} [[length overall|long overall]] and {{convert|104.45|m|ftin}} [[length between perpendiculars|between perpendiculars]], has a beam of {{convert|18|m|ftin}} and draws {{convert|4.9|m|ftin}} of water with a [[Displacement (ship)|displacement]] of {{convert|5892|t|LT}}.<ref name=\"seaweb\" /> Her [[gross tonnage]] is 8,445; [[net tonnage]] 2,573; and [[deadweight tonnage]] 1,177 tonnes. The ship's hull and propulsion system are strengthened for navigation in ice-covered waters according to the [[DNV GL]] [[ice class]] E4.<ref name=\"dnv\" /><ref name=\"ice class\" group=\"note\">Equivalent to the highest [[Finnish-Swedish ice class]] for merchant ships, 1A Super</ref>\n\nBuilt to cater to the [[star (classification)|five-star]] luxury cruise market, interiors on the ''RCGS Resolute''{{'}}s six passenger-accessible decks were designed by the German architect [[Wilfried K\u00f6hnemann]].<ref name=\"id\" /> The vessel has 88 outside cabins and, above the bridge deck, four suites for a total of 184 passengers served by a crew of 125. Public spaces include a restaurant, multiple lounges, and a 78-seat theater. The ship carries 14 [[Zodiac inflatable boat]]s to take passengers ashore during expedition cruises.<ref name=\"Hapag\" /> \n\nThe ship's propulsion system consists of two [[straight-8 engine|eight-cylinder]] [[MaK]] 8M453C four-stroke medium-speed [[diesel engine]]s, each rated {{convert|2940|kW|hp}} at 600{{nbsp}}rpm, driving two [[controllable pitch propeller]]s. Onboard electrical power is generated by two {{convert|1160|kW|hp|adj=on}} [[straight-6 engine|six-cylinder]] MaK 6M332 auxiliary diesel generators and two {{convert|1040|kW|hp|adj=on}} main engine driven shaft generators. For maneuvering in ports, the ship has a {{convert|700|kW|hp|adj=on}} transverse [[bow thruster]].<ref name=\"seaweb\" /><ref name=\"dnv\" /> ''RCGS Resolute'' has a service speed of {{convert|16|kn}} and a cruising range of {{convert|8600|nmi}}.<ref name=\"Hapag\" />\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== ''Society Adventurer'' ===\n\nIn December 1989, the German cruise ship company [[Discoverer Reederei]] ordered a $75 million cruise ship from the Finnish shipbuilder [[Rauma Yards]] (formerly [[Rauma-Repola]]; later [[Finnyards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://meriteollisuus.teknologiateollisuus.fi/sites/meriteollisuus/files/inline-files/Meriteoll_historiikki_web.pdf|title=Kun rauta kelluu \u2014 V\u00e4l\u00e4hdyksi\u00e4 suomalaisen meriteollisuuden vuosisadasta|publisher=Meriteollisuus|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>) for its US-based subsidiary [[Society Expeditions]]. The ship, launched on 5 January 1991 as ''Society Adventurer'',<ref name=\"dnv\" /> was intended for adventure-style expedition cruises to remote destinations such as [[Antarctica]] and had, among other features, an ice-strengthened hull. However, Discoverer Reederei was unable to take delivery of the vessel in the following summer due to financial troubles and also had to cancel a [[sister ship]] that had already been contracted.<ref name=\"id\" /> As a result, the ownership of the vessel was transferred to Rauma Yards's newly-established Bahamas-registered subsidiary, Society Adventurer Shipping Company, on 7 June 1991.<ref name=\"dnv\" /> While on a lay-up at the yard, ''Society Adventurer'' was inspected by a number of parties interested in acquiring the vessel, among them the future [[president of the United States]] [[Donald Trump]].<ref name=\"id\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ls24.fi/uutiset/donald-trump-kavi-raumalla-laivakaupoilla-nayttelijavaimo-naytti-poseeraamisen-mallia|title=Donald Trump k\u00e4vi Raumalla laivakaupoilla - n\u00e4yttelij\u00e4vaimo n\u00e4ytti poseeraamisen mallia|work=L\u00e4nsi-Suomi|date=21 May 2016|accessdate=4 April 2020|language=fi}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.satakunnankansa.fi/satakunta/donald-trump-piipahti-1992-raumalla-laivakaupoilla-ja-tansseissa-13973980|title=Donald Trump piipahti 1992 Raumalla laivakaupoilla ja tansseissa|work=Satakunnan Kansa|date=9 November 2016|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Hanseatic'' ===\n[[File:Hanseatic 5.jpg|thumb|left|''Hanseatic'' sporting the classic [[Hamburg Atlantic Line]] livery in Nuuk, Greenland, in 2008.]]\n\nIn 1993, the ship was chartered and shortly afterwards purchased by the German expedition cruise operator [[Hanseatic Tours]].<ref name=\"id\" /> The company had been established two years earlier by [[Dirk Moldenhauer]], who had been the last captain of [[German Atlantic Line]]'s cruise ship [[TS Maxim Gorkiy|''Hanseatic'']] in 1973 and later acquired rights to the classic Hamburg Atlantic Line logo, livery and the name \"Hanseatic\".<ref name=\"simplonpc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.simplonpc.co.uk/HamburgAtlantik.html|title=Hamburg Atlantik Line/Deutsche Atlantik Line/Hanseatic Tours|accessdate=4 April 2020|author=Ian Boyle|work=Simplon Postcards}}</ref> ''Society Adventurer'' was renamed ''Hanseatic'' on 23 March 1993,<ref name=\"schwerdtner\">{{cite|title=German Luxury Ocean Liners: From Kaiser Wilhelm Der Grosse to Aidastella|last=Schwerdtner|first=Nils|publisher=Amberley Publishing|year=2013|}}</ref> becoming the fourth ship to bear the name, and the original blue-yellow-white Discoverer Reederei livery was replaced with the white hull and red decorative stripes.<ref name=\"id\" /> The vessel's maiden cruise from [[Hamburg]] to [[Sevilla]] began on 27 March 1993.<ref name=\"fof\">{{cite web|url=http://www.faktaomfartyg.se/society_adventurer_1991.htm|title=M/S Society Adventurer|work=Fakta om Fartyg|last=Asklander|first=Micke|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> When Hanseatic Tours was merged with [[Hapag-Lloyd Cruises]] in 1997, ''Hanseatic'' retained her original name as well as Hamburg Atlantic Line livery and funnel logo until rebranding in 2011.<ref name=\"schwerdtner\" /><ref name=\"seatrade\">{{cite web|url=https://www.seatrade-cruise.com/news-headlines/former-hanseatic-leaves-germany-after-long-career-hapag-lloyd|title=Former Hanseatic leaves Germany after long career with Hapag-Lloyd|work=Seatrade Cruise News|publisher=Informa Markets|date=8 October 2018|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n''Hanseatic'' remained in Hapag-Lloyd's fleet until 2018. Over the ship's 25-year career and a total of 667 cruises, she made 128 expeditions to Antarctica, two voyages to the [[Northern Sea Route]] (Northeast Passage), and transited the full length of the [[Northwest Passage]] 11 times.<ref name=\"seatrade\" /> The latter is a record number for passenger ships, exceeded only by the Russian [[icebreaker]] ''[[Kapitan Khlebnikov]]'' which is also used for expedition cruises.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spri.cam.ac.uk/resources/infosheets/northwestpassage.pdf|title=Transits of the Northwest Passage to the end of the 2019 navigation season|publisher=Scott Polar Research Institute|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> ''Hanseatic'' also holds the record for having been further north among passenger-carrying ships that are not icebreakers: on 26 August 2014, the vessel reached {{Coord|85|40.7|N|135|39.6|E|display=inline}}, {{convert|259|nmi}} from the [[North Pole]], due to unusually easy ice conditions in the Russian Arctic.<ref name=\"seatrade\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.travelpulse.com/news/cruise/expedition-ship-hanseatic-sets-new-record-for-passenger-ships.html|title=Expedition Ship Hanseatic Sets New Record for Passenger Ships|publisher=Travel Pulse|date=28 August 2014|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== ''RCGS Resolute'' ===\n\nIn June 2017, the Canada-based cruise ship operator [[One Ocean Expeditions]] announced that it would expand its fleet of expedition cruise ships with a long-term charter of the former ''Hanseatic''. The ship would be renamed ''RCGS Resolute'' after the 1850-built [[Royal Navy]] Arctic exploration vessel [[HMS Resolute|HMS ''Resolute'']] as well as the [[Inuit]] hamlet [[Resolute, Nunavut|Resolute]] in [[Nunavut]]. Furthermore, the ship would carry the initials of the [[Royal Canadian Geographic Society]] (RCGS) with whom One Ocean Expeditions had partnered.<ref name=\"oneocean_july2017\">{{cite web|url=https://discover.oneoceanexpeditions.com/rcgs-resolute/|title=One Ocean Expeditions Expands Fleet and Operations with New Vessel: RCGS RESOLUTE|publisher=One Ocean Expeditions|date=June 2017|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> After concluding her career with Hapag-Lloyd and a brief drydocking in Germany, the vessel headed to Canada in October 2018 under her new name and with new livery.<ref name=\"seatrade\" />\n\nIn 2019, the company's financial difficulties began to surface with the sudden withdrawal of the Russian research vessels ''[[Akademik Ioffe]]'' and ''[[Akademik Sergey Vavilov]]'' chartered from the [[Shirshov Institute of Oceanology]]. Although One Ocean Expeditions initially called the Russian owner's action a contract violation, it was later revealed that the company had failed to pay charter and fueling fees to the intermediate charterer Terragelida Ship Management which had then terminated the contract.<ref name=\"guardian_oct2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.pe.ca/business/regional-business/shipping-news-one-ocean-expeditions-sails-into-troubled-waters-370614/|title=SHIPPING NEWS: One Ocean Expeditions sails into troubled waters|date=31 October 2019|accessdate=5 April 2020|work=The Guardian|publisher=Saltwire Network}}</ref> This left One Ocean Expeditions with just one ship, ''RCGS Resolute''. In August, she was briefly arrested in [[Iqaluit]] over a C$100,000 payment dispute. While this issue was reportedly solved quickly,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.maritime-executive.com/article/cruise-ship-briefly-arrested-in-nunavut|title= Cruise Ship Briefly Arrested in Nunavut|publisher=The Maritime Executive|date=19 August 2019|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> another arrest over non-payment of services and crew wages followed in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]] next month. Finally, in October One Ocean Expeditions was forced to cancel an Antarctic cruise midway after the vessel could not be refueled due to the company's non-payment of outstanding debts. Shortly after the ship's 140 passengers disembarked, ''RCGS Resolute'' was detained in [[Buenos Aires]] over \"significant debt\".<ref name=\"guardian_oct2018\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/one-ocean-expeditions-ship-detained-1.5370649|title=Ship belonging to troubled B.C. expedition cruise company detained in Argentina|date=24 November 2019|publisher=CBC|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> The company entered administration in January 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cruisecritic.co.uk/news/4955/|title=One Ocean Expeditions Cruise Line Collapses|work=CruiseCritic|publisher=The Independent Traveler|date=13 January 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March 2020, ''RCGS Resolute'' left Buenos Aires after a total of US$3.6 million of outstanding debt was paid to fuel suppliers, ship agents and crew members.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thechronicleherald.ca/business/local-business/shipping-news-some-cruise-companies-scrap-schedule-others-continue-on-425502/|title=SHIPPING NEWS: Some cruise companies scrap schedule, others continue on|work=The Chronicle Herald|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Incidents ==\n\n=== 1996 grounding === \n\nOn 29 August 1996, ''Hanseatic'' ran aground in [[Simpson Strait]] in the Canadian Arctic. The vessel was eleven days into an eastbound transit along the Northwest Passage with 149 passengers and 110 crew, and had stopped at [[Gjoa Haven]] to let passengers ashore. Unknowingly to the crew, a green buoy marking a shallow shoal had not been removed after the previous navigating season and, over the winter months, had been moved to the northeast by about {{convert|200|m|yd}} by drifting ice. Shortly after departure, ''Hanseatic'' ran aground on the shoal at {{Coord|68|33.75|N|97|32.2|W|display=inline}}.<ref name=\"1996report\">{{cite web|url=https://bst-tsb.gc.ca/ENG/rapports-reports/marine/1996/m96h0016/M96H0016.pdf|title=Grounding of passenger vessel \"Hanseatic\" at Simpson Strait, Northwest Territories, 29 August 1996 (report number M96H0016)|publisher=Transport Safety Board of Canada|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nWith no danger of the vessel sinking, ''Hanseatic''{{'}}s passengers were allowed to explore the nearby islands using the ship's boats until the Russian icebreaker ''[[Kapitan Dranitsyn]]'' arrived to pick up the passengers on 5 September and continue the Northwest Passage expedition under charter by Hanseatic Tours. ''Hanseatic'' itself was successfully refloated on 8 September. While the ship's hull was damaged during the grounding, no oil spilled to the sea and there were no injuries among the passengers or the crew.<ref name=\"1996report\" />\n\n=== 1997 grounding ===\n\nOn 14 July 1997, ''Hanseatic'' was grounded on a sand bank in [[Murchisonfjorden]] in [[Svalbard]] with 145 passengers onboard.<ref>{{cite book|title=Navigation Safety and Risk Assessment Challenges in the High North|last1=Marchenko|first1=N.|last2=Borch|first2=O.J.|last3=Andreassen|first3=N.|last4=Kuznetsova|first4=S.Yu.|last5=Ingimundarson|first5=V.|last6=Jakobsen|first6=U.|work=Marine Navigation: Proceedings of the 12th International Conference on Marine Navigation and Safety of Sea Transportation (TransNav 2017), June 21-23, 2017, Gdynia, Poland|publisher=CRC Press|year=2017|page=345|isbn=978-13-5158-218-6}}</ref><ref name=\"penguins\">{{cite book|last=Wright|first=Christopher|title=Of Penguins and Polar Bears: A History of Cold Water Cruising|year=2020|publisher=The History Press|ISBN=978-07-5099-456-9}}</ref> No injuries nor damage to the ship was reported, and the passengers were again taken to explore nearby islands on ''Hanseatic''{{'}}s Zodiac boats while awaiting evacuation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/0e7c429f30ac4d87307fb0eea3de2220|title=Cruise ship stuck in Arctic after running aground|date=14 July 1997|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> By 17 July, the ship had been refloated and was heading towards [[Longyearbyen]] for inspection.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.travelweekly.com/Cruise-Travel/Hanseatic-Grounded-in-the-Arctic|title=Hanseatic Grounded in the Arctic|date=17 July 1997|publisher=Travel Weekly|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 2005 grounding ===\n\nIn August 2005, ''Hanseatic'' ran aground near the island of [[Lur\u00f8ya, Nordland|Lur\u00f8ya]] on the Norwegian coast, just south of the [[Arctic Circle]], with 160 passengers onboard. While the vessel was not in danger of sinking despite a {{convert|5|m|ft|adj=on}} hole in one of her [[ballast water]] tank, the passengers and part of the crew was nonetheless evacuated.<ref name=\"penguins\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ranablad.no/nyheter/cruiseskip-evakuert/s/1-93-1706219|title=Cruiseskip evakuert|language=no|work=Rana Blad|date=22 August 2005|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 2013 drydock fire ===\n\nOn 13 June 2013, a fire broke out in ''Hanseatic''{{'}}s engine room due to [[hot work]] in one of the ballast water tanks while the ship was in a [[drydock]] at the Bredo Shipyard in [[Bremerhaven]]. Due to delays in drydocking and additional repairs required by the fire, four cruises between 17 June and 1 August had to be cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/travel/news/2013/06/25/hapag-lloyd-hanseatic-fire/2455171/|title=Hapag-Lloyd cancels more cruises due to shipyard fire|work=USA Today|date=25 June 2013|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 2020 collision with Venezuelan patrol boat ''Naiguat\u00e1'' ===\n\nIn the early hours of 30 March 2020 ''RCGS Resolute'' was drifting in International waters, near [[Willemstad]], [[Curacao]], some {{convert|60|nmi}} off the country's northern coast, when the Venezuelan Coast Guard patrol boat  {{ship|Venezuelan patrol boat|Naiguat\u00e1||2}}, also known by her hull number GC-23, approached her. The Venezuelan ship ordered the cruise ship to follow her to [[Puerto Moreno]] on [[Margarita Island]], located to the east, accusing her of violating the country's territorial waters. Gun shots were fired and, shortly thereafter, the navy vessel approached the starboard side at speed with an angle of 135\u00b0 and purposely collided with ''RCGS Resolute''. The navy vessel continued to ram the starboard bow in an apparent attempt to turn the ship's head towards Venezuelan territorial waters. While ''RCGS Resolute'' sustained minor damage, not affecting vessel's seaworthiness, the navy vessel suffered severe damage while making contact with the [[ice class|ice-strengthened]] [[bulbous bow]] of the expedition cruise vessel ''RCGS Resolute'' and started to take water.<ref name=jpost20200403>{{cite news |url=https://www.jpost.com/International/Venezuelan-warship-shoots-rams-into-German-cruise-vessel-before-sinking-623422 |title=Venezuelan warship shoots, rams into German cruise vessel before sinking |work=[[Jerusalem Post]] |date=3 April 2020 |access-date=3 April 2020 }}</ref> Ultimately ''Naiguat\u00e1'' sank, leaving the 44 naval personnel to be rescued by another vessel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fleetmon.com/maritime-news/2020/29297/cruise-ship-sunk-venezuelan-navy-ship-and-fled-pro/?fbclid=|title=Cruise Ship Sunk Venezuelan Navy Ship after being Fired at and Rammed. Don\u2019t mess with Resolute.|last=Voytenko|first=Mikhail|date=1 April 2020|website=Fleet Mon|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>{{Better source|date=April 2020|reason=Non-NPOV}}<ref name=jpost20200403/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{commonscat|IMO 9000168}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Hapag-Lloyd Cruises}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:RCGS Resolute}}\n[[Category:Cruise ships]]\n[[Category:1991 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Rauma, Finland]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 2020]]\n", "name_user": "Tupsumato", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2020 collision with Venezuelan patrol boat Naiguat\u00e1:add some details; this needs to be revised at some point...", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RCGS_Resolute"}
{"title_page": "Montrose, Iowa", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Montrose, Iowa\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = Montrose iowa.jpg\n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map = Lee_County_Iowa_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Montrose_Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Montrose, Iowa\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             =\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = {{USA}}\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = {{flag|Iowa}}\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Iowa|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Lee County, Iowa|Lee]]\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = \n|leader_name              = \n|leader_title1            = \n|leader_name1             = \n|established_title        = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name =\"Gazetteer files\"/>\n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 2.95\n|area_land_km2            = 2.90\n|area_water_km2           = 0.05\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 1.14\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 1.12\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.02\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_est           = 800\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name =\"FactFinder\"/>\n|population_total         = 898\n|population_density_km2   = 309.6\n|population_density_sq_mi = auto\n|timezone                 = [[North American Central Time Zone|Central (CST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -6\n|timezone_DST             = CDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -5\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 162\n|elevation_ft             = 531\n|coordinates              = {{coord|40|31|46|N|91|24|58|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 52639\n|area_code                = [[Area code 319|319]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 19-53760\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0459199\n|website                  = \n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=February 23, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Montrose''' is a city in [[Lee County, Iowa|Lee County]], [[Iowa]], United States. The population was 898 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]]. The town is located on the [[Mississippi River]]. It is part of the [[Fort Madison, Iowa|Fort Madison]]&ndash;[[Keokuk, Iowa|Keokuk]], IA-[[Missouri|MO]] [[Fort Madison-Keokuk micropolitan area|Micropolitan Statistical Area]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Lee ft dm rapids 1837.jpg|thumb|left|[[Robert E. Lee]] map of the head of the [[Des Moines Rapids]], 1837, showing Fort Des Moines No. 1, later Montrose, Iowa.]]\nThe area around Montrose has been occupied continuously since at least the 1780s, when [[Quashquame]]'s village was established nearby. The area was strategically important because it is at the head of the [[Des Moines Rapids]], a major impediment to river traffic that caused large boats to land in this area and transfer freight overland to avoid the rapids.<ref>Hallwas, John E. (2001) ''Keokuk and the Great Dam.'' Arcadia Publishing, Chicago.</ref> Montrose was the location of Fort Des Moines No. 1, a military post from 1834\u20131837. From 1839-1846 Montrose was the home of many members of the [[Church of Christ (Latter Day Saints)|Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints]].  This was especially true in 1839 when many people lived in an abandoned barracks at Montrose that served as a good short term residence while homes were being built in [[Nauvoo, Illinois|Nauvoo]].  Among Montrose's residents at this time were [[Brigham Young]], [[Wilford Woodruff]] and [[Erastus Snow]]. Despite legends that the streets of Montrose were aligned to allow a direct view of the [[Nauvoo Temple]] across the Mississippi River in Illinois,<ref>Wills, Christopher. Associated Press (AP), December 7, 2007.</ref> the streets actually align with the 1834 layout of Fort Des Moines.<ref>several maps exist of Fort Des Moines showing the same alignment as modern Montrose, including one drawn by [[Robert E. Lee]], (1837) ''Map of the Des Moines Rapids of the Mississippi River. Surveyed by Lt. R. E. Lee, September 1837.'' National Archives, Washington, D. C.</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nMontrose's longitude and latitude coordinates<br>in decimal form are 40.529532, -91.415995.<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|1.14|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, of which, {{convert|1.12|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is land and {{convert|0.02|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is water.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web|title=US Gazetteer files 2010|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2012-05-11|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120702145235/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt|archivedate=2012-07-02}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations\n|title= Historical populations\n|type= USA\n|align= right\n|1850|454\n|1870|905\n|1880|983\n|1890|778\n|1900|748\n|1910|708\n|1920|549\n|1930|621\n|1940|592\n|1950|643\n|1960|632\n|1970|735\n|1980|1038\n|1990|957\n|2000|957\n|2010|898\n|2018|800\n|source=<center>U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref></center>\n|footnote=Source:{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|title=American FactFinder|access-date=2020-03-29|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212063637/http://factfinder.census.gov/|archive-date=2020-02-12|url-status=dead}} and [http://data.iowadatacenter.org/datatables/PlacesAll/plpopulation18502000.pdf Iowa Data Center]\n}}\n\n===2010 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name =\"FactFinder\">{{cite web|title=American FactFinder|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212234628/http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|url-status=dead|archive-date=2020-02-12|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2012-05-11}}</ref> of 2010, there were 898 people, 359 households, and 242 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was {{convert|801.8|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 405 housing units at an average density of {{convert|361.6|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The racial makeup of the city was 98.2% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.4% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.3% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], and 1.0% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 0.6% of the population.\n\nThere were 359 households of which 26.2% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 51.8% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 10.6% had a female householder with no husband present, 5.0% had a male householder with no wife present, and 32.6% were non-families. 28.7% of all households were made up of individuals and 13.9% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.37 and the average family size was 2.86.\n\nThe median age in the city was 47.4 years. 18.5% of residents were under the age of 18; 7.2% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 21.2% were from 25 to 44; 32.6% were from 45 to 64; and 20.6% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the city was 48.9% male and 51.1% female.\n\n===2000 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212221153/http://factfinder.census.gov/main.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2020-02-12|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=American FactFinder}}</ref> of 2000, there were 957 people, 374 households, and 255 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was 852.1 people per square mile (329.9/km\u00b2). There were 399 housing units at an average density of 355.3 per square mile (137.5/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 97.81% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.10% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.73% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.10% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.21% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 1.04% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 0.84% of the population.\n\nThere were 374 households out of which 31.8% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 54.5% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 9.4% had a female householder with no husband present, and 31.8% were non-families. 29.9% of all households were made up of individuals and 16.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.44 and the average family size was 3.00.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 24.3% under the age of 18, 7.0% from 18 to 24, 25.3% from 25 to 44, 24.7% from 45 to 64, and 18.7% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 41 years. For every 100 females, there were 87.6 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 84.2 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $35,341, and the median income for a family was $40,865. Males had a median income of $30,855 versus $21,845 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $17,010. About 7.0% of families and 8.9% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 10.9% of those under age 18 and 6.8% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Education==\nIt is served by [[Central Lee Community School District]].<ref>\"[https://educateiowa.gov/sites/files/ed/documents/SDRP2017_CENTRAL%20LEE.pdf Central Lee].\" [[Iowa Department of Education]]. Retrieved on September 16, 2018.</ref>\n\n==Notable people==<!--consensus reached to standardize this heading per WP:WikiProject Cities/US Guideline -->\n\n<!-- NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * * * * * * * * * *NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * NOTICE\nOnly people who already have a Wikipedia article may appear here as Notable people. This establishes notability.\nThe biographical article should say how they are associated with THIS CITY examples = born, raised, residing etc.\nAn external reliable source of their association with THIS CITY should be cited in their Article and MUST be cited HERE.\nAll others will be deleted without further explanation.\nAlphabetical by last name please. Use a short one line description of Notability.\nIf the person you think is Notable and does not have a Wikipedia Article for themselves create one.\nGuidelines for the Notability of a person can be found by entering WP:PEOPLE in the wiki search.\nGuidelines on what is needed and how to write the Article can be found  by ente