://books.google.com/books?id=mDZbcAlOZ3QC&pg=PA29 |date=1 January 2012 |publisher=Int'l Business Publications |isbn=978-1-4387-7095-6 |page=29 |access-date=25 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425122834/https://books.google.com/books?id=mDZbcAlOZ3QC&pg=PA29 |archive-date=25 April 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>}} <br /> [[Big tent]]<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3fctDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT395&dq=SNP+big+tent&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwienZ-ev-PaAhWMLsAKHabMAtIQ6AEILTAB#v=onepage&q=SNP%20big%20tent&f=false A Nation Changed?: The SNP and Scotland Ten Years On] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180501160810/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3fctDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT395&dq=SNP+big+tent&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwienZ-ev-PaAhWMLsAKHabMAtIQ6AEILTAB#v=onepage&q=SNP%20big%20tent&f=false |date=1 May 2018 }}. Edited by Gerry Hassan and Simon Barrow. Chapter author - Joyce McMillan. Published in 2017, in Glasgow, Scotland. Published by Bell and Bain Ltd. Retrieved via Google Books.</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= Sim |first= Philip |date= 16 May 2019 |title= Are Joanna Cherry's claims of SNP 'infighting' true? |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-48295427 |work= BBC News |access-date= 14 August 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190816000100/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-48295427 |archive-date= 16 August 2019 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= Massie |first= Alex |date= 25 June 2017 |title= So what, exactly, is the point of the SNP? |url= https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/so-what-exactly-is-the-point-of-the-snp-b5wxh85ll |work= The Times |access-date= 14 August 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190814013717/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/so-what-exactly-is-the-point-of-the-snp-b5wxh85ll |archive-date= 14 August 2019 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n| european = [[European Free Alliance]]\n| colours = {{Color box|{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} Yellow\n| seats1_title = [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] ([[List of MPs for constituencies in Scotland (2019\u2013)|Scottish seats]])\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|47|59|background-color=#DDDDDD|hex={{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}}}\n| seats2_title = [[Scottish Parliament]]<ref name=\"bbcelection2016\">{{cite web|author1=BBC|authorlink1=BBC|title=Scotland Parliament election 2016|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election/2016/scotland|website=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=16 November 2017|date=2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171127234658/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election/2016/scotland|archive-date=27 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|61|129|background-color=#DDDDDD|hex={{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}}}\n| seats3_title = [[Local government in Scotland]]<ref name=\"localcouncil\">{{cite web|url=http://www.opencouncildata.co.uk/index.php|title=Local Council Political Compositions|date=24 October 2019|publisher=Open Council Date UK|accessdate=24 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170930131243/http://www.opencouncildata.co.uk/index.php|archive-date=30 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|418|1227|background-color=#DDDDDD|hex={{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}}} <!--Please see (and update if needed) https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Political_make-up_of_local_councils_in_the_United_Kingdom#Unitary_authorities_.28Scotland.29.--> <!-- Last updated using data from 9 May 2017, SNP page updated 5 April 2020 -->\n}}\n\nThe '''Scottish National Party''' ('''SNP'''; {{lang-gd|P\u00e0rtaidh N\u00e0iseanta na h-Alba}}, {{lang-sco|Scots National Pairtie}}) is a [[Scottish nationalism|Scottish nationalist]],<ref name=\"Abedi2004\">{{cite book |author=Amir Abedi |title=Anti-political Establishment Parties: A Comparative Analysis |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B8oPfqRUqOYC&pg=PA72 |year=2004 |publisher=Psychology Press |isbn=978-0-415-31961-4 |page=72 |access-date=25 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426000828/https://books.google.com/books?id=B8oPfqRUqOYC&pg=PA72 |archive-date=26 April 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Political Systems of the World |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DIkWJ3psB2gC&pg=PA122 |publisher=Allied Publishers |isbn=978-81-7023-307-7 |page=122 |access-date=25 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624003313/https://books.google.com/books?id=DIkWJ3psB2gC&pg=PA122 |archive-date=24 June 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[social democracy|social-democratic]]<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"Hepburn20139\"/><ref name=\"Lingard\"/> [[list of political parties in Scotland|political party]] in [[Scotland]]. The SNP supports and campaigns for [[Scottish independence]] within the [[European Union]].<ref name=\"Schrijver2006\"/><ref name=\"O'Neill2014\">{{cite book |author=Michael O'Neill |title=Devolution and British Politics |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-OahAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA92 |date=22 May 2014 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-317-87365-5 |page=92 |access-date=25 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160504063039/https://books.google.com/books?id=-OahAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA92 |archive-date=4 May 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> It is the third-largest political party by membership in the [[United Kingdom]], behind the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] and the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]; it is the third-largest by overall representation in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]], behind the Conservative Party and the Labour Party; and it is the largest political party in [[Scotland]], where it has the most seats in the [[Scottish Parliament]] and 47 out of the 59 Scottish seats in the House of Commons of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]]. The current Scottish National Party leader, [[Nicola Sturgeon]], has served as [[First Minister of Scotland]] since November 2014.\n\nFounded in 1934 with the amalgamation of the [[National Party of Scotland]] and the [[Scottish Party]], the party has had continuous parliamentary [[List of Scottish National Party MPs|representation in Westminster]] since [[Winnie Ewing]] won the [[1967 Hamilton by-election]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Heisey |first1=Monica |title=Making the case for an \"aye\" in Scotland |url=http://www.queensu.ca/alumnireview/making-case-aye-scotland |website=Alumni Review |publisher=[[Queen's University at Kingston|Queen's University]] |accessdate=4 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150505143416/http://queensu.ca/alumnireview/making-case-aye-scotland |archivedate=5 May 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> With the establishment of the devolved Scottish Parliament in 1999, the SNP became the second-largest party, serving two terms as the [[Opposition (parliamentary)|opposition]]. The SNP gained power at the [[2007 Scottish Parliament election]], forming a [[minority government]], before going on to win the [[2011 Scottish Parliament election|2011 Parliament election]], after which it formed [[Scottish Parliament|Holyrood]]'s first [[majority government]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2011/may/11/scottish-msps-sworn-in-holyrood |title=MSPs sworn in at Holyrood after SNP landslide |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=11 May 2011 |accessdate=12 July 2011 |location=London |first=Severin |last=Carrell |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219035735/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2011/may/11/scottish-msps-sworn-in-holyrood |archive-date=19 February 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> It was reduced back to being a minority government at the [[2016 Scottish Parliament election|2016 election]].\n\nThe SNP is the largest political party in Scotland in terms of both seats in the Westminster and Holyrood parliaments, and membership, reaching 125,482 members as of December 2019, 47 [[Member of Parliament|MPs]], 61 [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|MSPs]] and over 400 local councillors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/topics/8201e79d-41c0-48f1-b15c-d7043ac30517/scotland-local-elections-2017|title=Scotland local elections 2017|work=[[BBC News Online]]|access-date=21 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170902143816/http://www.bbc.com/news/topics/8201e79d-41c0-48f1-b15c-d7043ac30517/scotland-local-elections-2017|archive-date=2 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The SNP is a member of the [[European Free Alliance]] (EFA). The party does not have any members of the [[House of Lords]], as it has always maintained a position of [[Reform of the House of Lords#Abolition|objecting to an unelected upper house]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/4269814.stm|title=SNP maintains peerage opposition|date=22 September 2005|work=BBC News|access-date=21 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170804220230/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/4269814.stm|archive-date=4 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-33695476 |title=House of Lords should be scrapped, says SNP |work=BBC News |date=28 July 2015 |accessdate=15 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170511021805/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-33695476 |archive-date=11 May 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{Main|History of the Scottish National Party}}\n===Foundation and Early Breakthroughs (1934-1970)===\nThe SNP was formed in 1934 through the merger of the [[National Party of Scotland]] and the [[Scottish Party]], with [[James Graham, 6th Duke of Montrose|The Duke of Montrose]] and [[Robert Bontine Cunninghame Graham]] as its first, joint, president.<ref>{{cite journal| first=Robbie| last=Dinwoodie| title=From radicals and Tartan Tories to the party of government| journal=Herald Scotland| date=7 April 2014| url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/politics/wider-political-news/from-radicals-and-tartan-tories-to-the-party-of-government.23890738| accessdate=10 July 2019| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518033243/http://www.heraldscotland.com/politics/wider-political-news/from-radicals-and-tartan-tories-to-the-party-of-government.23890738| archive-date=18 May 2015| url-status=live}}</ref> [[Alexander MacEwen|Sir Alexander MacEwen]] was its first chairman.<ref>{{cite book |first1=James |last1=Mitchell |first2=Gerry |last2=Hassan |title=Scottish National Party Leaders |place=London |publisher=Biteback |year=2016 |isbn=978-1-7859-0092-1}}</ref> [[Douglas Young (classicist)|Professor Douglas Young]], who was the leader of the Scottish National Party from 1942 to 1945 campaigned for the Scottish people to refuse [[conscription]] and his activities were popularly vilified as undermining the [[Military history of the United Kingdom during World War II|British war effort]] against the [[Axis powers]]. Young was imprisoned for refusing to be conscripted.\n\nThe party suffered its first split during this period with John MacCormick leaving the party in 1942, owing to his failure to change the party's policy from supporting all out independence to [[Devolution in the United Kingdom|Home Rule]] at that year's conference in Glasgow. McCormick went on to form the [[Scottish Covenant Association]], a non-partisan political organisation campaigning for the establishment of a devolved Scottish Assembly.\n\nHowever, wartime conditions also enabled the SNP's first parliamentary success at the [[1945 Motherwell by-election|Motherwell by-election]] in 1945, but [[Robert McIntyre]] MP lost the seat at the [[1945 United Kingdom general election|general election]] three months later. The 1950s were characterised by similarly low levels of support, and this made it difficult for the party to advance. Indeed, in most general elections they were unable to put up more than a handful of candidates.\n\nThe 1960s, however, offered more electoral successes, with candidates polling credibly at [[Glasgow Bridgeton by-election, 1961|Glasgow Bridgeton]] in 1961, [[1962 West Lothian by-election|West Lothian]] in 1962 and [[1967 Glasgow Pollok by-election|Glasgow Pollok]] in 1967. Indeed, this foreshadowed [[Winnie Ewing]]'s  surprise victory in [[1967 Hamilton by-election|a by-election]] at the previously safe [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] seat of [[Hamilton (UK Parliament constituency)|Hamilton]]. This brought the SNP to national prominence, leading to the establishment of the [[Royal Commission on the Constitution (United Kingdom)|Kilbrandon Commission]].\n\n=== Becoming a Major Force (1970s) ===\nDespite this breakthrough, the [[1970 United Kingdom general election|1970 general election]] was to prove a disappointment for the party as despite an increase in vote share, Ewing failed to retain her seat in Hamilton. The party did receive some consolation with the capture of the [[Western Isles (UK Parliament constituency)|Western Isles]], making [[Donald Stewart (MP)|Donald Stewart]] the party's only MP. This was to be the case until the [[1973 Glasgow Govan by-election|1973 by-election]] at [[Glasgow Govan (UK Parliament constituency)|Glasgow Govan]] where a hitherto safe Labour seat was claimed by [[Margo MacDonald]].\n\n1974 was to prove something of an [[annus mirabilis]] for the party as it deployed its highly effective ''[[It's Scotland's oil]]'' campaign<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.versobooks.com/blogs/4241-dilemmas-of-over-development-scottish-nationalism-and-the-future-of-the-union|title=Dilemmas of Over-Development: Scottish Nationalism and the Future of the Union|website=Versobooks.com|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>. The SNP gained 6 seats at the [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|February general election]] before hitting a high point in the [[October 1974 United Kingdom general election|October re-run]], polling almost a third of all votes in Scotland and returning 11 MPs to Westminster. Furthermore, during that year's [[1974 Scottish local elections|local elections]] the party claimed overall control of [[Cumbernauld and Kilsyth]]. \n\nThis success was to continue for much of the decade, and at the [[1977 Scottish local elections|1977 district elections]] the SNP saw victories at councils including [[East Kilbride (district)|East Kilbride]] and [[Falkirk Council|Falkirk]] and held the balance of power in [[1977 Glasgow City District Council election|Glasgow]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Faux|first=Ronald|url=|title=Labour lose control of Glasgow|date=4 May 1977|work=The Times, p. 1|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>. However, this level of support was not to last and by 1978 Labour revival was evident at three by-elections ([[1978 Glasgow Garscadden by-election|Glasgow Garscadden]], [[1978 Hamilton by-election|Hamilton]] and [[1978 Berwick and East Lothian by-election|Berwick and East Lothian]]) as well as the [[1978 Scottish regional elections|regional elections]].\n\nThis was to culminate when the party experienced a large drop in its support at the [[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979 general election]], precipitated by the party [[1979 vote of no confidence in the Callaghan ministry|bringing down]] the incumbent Labour minority government following the controversial failure of that year's [[1979 Scottish devolution referendum|devolution referendum]]. Reduced to just 2 MPs, the successes of October 1974 were not to be surpassed until the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]].\n\n=== Factional Divisions and Infighting (1980s) ===\nFollowing this defeat, a period of internal strike occurred within the party, culminating with the formation of two internal groups: the proto-fascist [[Siol nan Gaidheal|Siol nan Gaidhea]]<nowiki/>l<ref>{{Cite book|last=Devine, T. M. (Thomas Martin)|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1004568536|title=The Scottish nation : a modern history|isbn=978-0-7181-9673-8|location=London|oclc=1004568536}}</ref> and left-wing [[79 Group]]. Traditionalists within the party, centred around [[Winnie Ewing]], by this time an [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]], responded by establishing the [[Campaign for Nationalism in Scotland]] which sought to ensure that the primary objective of the SNP was campaigning for independence outwith a traditional left-right orientation, despite the fact that this would have undone the work of figures such as [[William Wolfe]], who developed a clearly [[Social democracy|social democratic]] policy platform throughout the 1970s.\n\nThese events ensured the success of a leadership motion at the party's annual conference of 1982, in [[Ayr]], despite the 79 Group being bolstered by the merger of [[Jim Sillars|Jim Sillars']] [[Scottish Labour Party (1976)|Scottish Labour Party (SLP)]] although this influx of ex-SLP members further shifted the characteristics of the party leftwards. Despite this, traditionalist figure [[Gordon Wilson (Scottish politician)|Gordon Wilson]] remained party leader through the electoral dissapointments of [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]] and [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]], where he lost his own [[Dundee East (UK Parliament constituency)|Dundee East]] seat won 13 years prior. \n\nThrough this period, Sillars grew influence in the party, developing a clear socio-economic platform including ''Independence in Europe,'' reversing the SNP's previous opposition to membership of the [[European Union|then-EEC]] which had been unsuccessful in a [[1975 United Kingdom European Communities membership referendum|1975 referendum]]. This position was enhanced further by Sillars reclaiming [[Glasgow Govan (UK Parliament constituency)|Glasgow Govan]] in a [[1988 Glasgow Govan by-election|by-election]] in 1988. \n\nDespite this moderation, the party did not join [[Scottish Labour|Labour]], the [[Scottish Liberal Democrats|Liberal Democrats]] and the [[Scottish Greens|Greens]] as well as civil society in the [[Scottish Constitutional Convention]] which developed a blueprint for a devolved [[Scottish Parliament]] due to the unwillingness of the convention to discuss independence as a constitutional option<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thetarge.co.uk/article/current-affairs/0165/ex-mp-scotland-in-trouble-if-lax-on-constitution|title=Ex-MP: Scotland \u2018in trouble\u2019 if lax on constitution - The Targe|website=thetarge.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>. \n\n=== First Salmond Era (1990s) ===\n[[Alex Salmond]] had been elected MP for [[Banff and Buchan (UK Parliament constituency)|Banff and Buchan]] in 1987, after the re-admittance of 79 Group members, and was able to seize the party leadership after Wilson's resignation in [[1990 Scottish National Party leadership election|1990]] after a contest with [[Margaret Ewing]]. This was a surprise victory as Ewing had the backing of much of the party establishment, including Sillars and then-Party Secretary [[John Swinney]]. The defection of Labour MP [[Dick Douglas]] further evidenced the party's clear left-wing positioning, particularly regarding opposition to the [[Poll tax (Great Britain)|poll tax]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-27388579|title=Former MP Dick Douglas dies aged 82|date=2014-05-13|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-GB}}</ref>. Despite this, Salmond's leadership was unable to avert a fourth successive general election disappointment in [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]] with the party reduced back from 5 to 3 MPs.\n\nThe mid-90s offered some successes for the party, with [[North East Scotland (European Parliament constituency)|North East Scotland]] being gained at the [[1994 European Parliament election|1994 European elections]] and the party securing a [[1995 Perth and Kinross by-election|by-election]] at [[Perth and Kinross (UK Parliament constituency)|Perth and Kinross]] in 1995 after a near miss at [[1994 Monklands East by-election|Monklands East]] the previous year.\n\n1997 offered the party's most successful [[1997 United Kingdom general election|general election]] for 23 years, although in the face of the Labour landslide the party was unable to match either 1974 election. That September, the party joined with the other members of the [[Scottish Constitutional Convention]] in the successful Yes-Yes campaign in the [[1997 Scottish devolution referendum|devolution referendum]] which lead to the establishment of a [[Scottish Parliament]] with tax-varying powers.\n\nBy 1999, the [[1999 Scottish Parliament election|first elections]] to the parliament were being held, although the party suffered a disappointing result, gaining just 35 MSPs in the face of Salmond's unpopular '[[Kosovo]] Broadcast' which opposed [[NATO intervention in Kosovo|NATO intervention]] in the country<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/politics-anti-bombing-salmond-hits-an-all-time-low-with-voters-1086961.html|title=Politics: Anti-bombing Salmond hits an all-time low with voters|date=1999-04-13|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>.\n\n=== Opposing Labour-Liberal Democrat Coalitions (1999-2007) ===\nThis meant that the party began as the official opposition in the parliament to a [[Dewar government|Labour-Liberal Democrat coalition government]]. Salmond found the move to a more consensual politics difficult and sought a return to Westminster, resigning the leadership in [[2000 Scottish National Party leadership election|2000]] with John Swinney, like Salmond a [[Fundamentalists and gradualists|gradualist]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Correspondent|first=Nick Britten, Scotland Political|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1349165/Scramble-to-lead-SNP-as-Salmond-quits.html|title=Scramble to lead SNP as Salmond quits|date=2000-07-17|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>, victorious in the ensuring leadership election<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/in_depth/uk_politics/2000/conferences/snp/938727.stm|title=BBC NEWS {{!}} In Depth {{!}} Conferences {{!}} SNP {{!}} Emphatic SNP win for Swinney|website=news.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>. Swinney's leadership proved ineffectual, with a loss of one MP in [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]] and a further reduction to 27 MSPs in [[2003 Scottish Parliament election|2003]] despite the [[Officegate]] scandal unseating previous [[First Minister of Scotland|First Minister]] [[Henry McLeish]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/in_depth/scotland/2001/mcleish_resignation/1645219.stm|title=McLeish steps down|date=2001-11-08|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-GB}}</ref>. However, the only parties to gain seats in that election where the [[Scottish Greens]] and the [[Scottish Socialist Party|Scottish Socialist Party (SSP)]] which like the SNP both support independence.\n\nAfter an unsuccessful [[2003 Scottish National Party leadership election|coup attempt]] in 2003, Swinney stepped down following disappointing results in the [[2004 European Parliament election|European elections of 2004]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/euro-poll-was-breaking-point-swinney-2507632|title=Euro poll was breaking point for Swinney|website=www.scotsman.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> with Salmond victorious in the [[2004 Scottish National Party leadership election|subsequent leadership contes]]<nowiki/>t despite initially refusing to be candidate<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/3622728.stm|title=Salmond named as new SNP leader|date=2004-09-03|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-GB}}</ref>. [[Nicola Sturgeon]] was elected Depute Leader and became the party's leader in the Scottish Parliament until Salmond to return at the next parliamentary election.\n\n===Salmond Government (2007-2014)===\nIn [[2007 Scottish Parliament election|2007]], the SNP emerged as the largest party in the Scottish Parliament with 47 of 129 seats, narrowly ousting the [[Scottish Labour Party]] with 46 seats and [[Alex Salmond]] becoming [[First Minister of Scotland|First Minister]] after ousting the Liberal Democrats in [[Gordon (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Gordon]]. The [[Scottish Green Party]] supported Salmond's election as First Minister, and his subsequent appointments of ministers, in return for early tabling of the [[Climate Change (Scotland) Act 2009|climate change bill]] and the SNP nominating a Green MSP to chair a parliamentary committee.<ref>{{cite news|title=SNP and Greens sign working deal|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/6646227.stm|publisher=BBC News Scotland|accessdate=16 March 2013|date=11 May 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301114950/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/6646227.stm|archive-date=1 March 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite this, Salmond's minority government tended to strike budget deals with the [[Scottish Conservatives|Conservatives]] to stay in office<ref>{{Cite news|last=Taylor|first=Brian|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-51227754|title=Could the SNP do a budget deal with the Tories?|date=2020-01-23|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-GB}}</ref>.\n\nIn [[2011 Scottish Parliament election|May 2011]], the SNP won an overall majority in the Scottish Parliament with 69 seats. This was a significant feat as the [[Additional member system (Scottish Parliament)|additional member system]] used for Scottish Parliament elections was specifically designed to prevent one party from winning an outright majority.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/alex-salmonds-snp-wins-majority-in-scottish-elections |title=SNP wins majority in Scottish elections |publisher=channel4.com |date= |accessdate=12 July 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712205311/http://www.channel4.com/news/alex-salmonds-snp-wins-majority-in-scottish-elections |archive-date=12 July 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.snp.org/our_party|title=Our Party|work=The SNP|access-date=2017-05-10|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609001024/https://www.snp.org/our_party|archive-date=9 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> This was followed by a reverse in the party's previous opposition to [[NATO]] membership at the party's annual conference in 2012<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-19993694|title=SNP votes to end anti-Nato policy|date=2012-10-19|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-GB}}</ref> despite Salmond's refusal to apologise for the Kosovo broadcast on the occasion of the [[2008 Kosovo declaration of independence|Kosovo Declaration of Independence]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/demand-for-alex-salmond-apology-over-969199|title=Demand For Alex Salmond Apology Over Kosovo|last=Dailyrecord.co.uk|date=2008-02-19|website=dailyrecord|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>.\n\nThis majority enabled the SNP government to hold a [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|referendum on Scottish independence]] in 2014. The \"No\" vote prevailed in a close-fought campaign, prompting the resignation of First Minister [[Alex Salmond]]. Forty-five percent of Scottish voters cast their ballots for independence, with the \"Yes\" side receiving less support than late polling predicted.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/sep/19/alex-salmond-resigns-first-minister-for-scotland|agency=The Guardian|title=Alex Salmond resigns as first minister after Scotland rejects independence|date=19 September 2014|accessdate=8 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403144910/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/sep/19/alex-salmond-resigns-first-minister-for-scotland|archive-date=3 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> This was suggested as due to Salmond's unpopularity among women<ref>{{Cite news|last=Goldhill|first=Olivia|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/scotland/11090459/Alex-Salmonds-female-problem-or-why-most-Scottish-women-wouldnt-trust-him-to-run-a-tea-party.html|title=Alex Salmond's 'female problem' - or why most Scottish women wouldn't trust him to run a tea party|date=2014-09-11|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> and Nicola Sturgeon won that [[2014 Scottish National Party leadership election|year's leadership election]] unopposed.\n\n=== Sturgeon Years (2014 onwards) ===\nThe SNP rebounded from the loss in the independence referendum at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 UK general election]], led by [[Nicola Sturgeon]]. The party went from holding six seats in the House of Commons to 56, mostly at the expense of the Labour Party. All but three of the fifty-nine constituencies in the country elected an SNP candidate in the party's most comprehensive electoral victory at any level.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2015-scotland-32635871|agency=BBC News|title=Election 2015: SNP wins 56 of 59 seats in Scots landslide|date=8 May 2015|accessdate=8 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150521003643/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2015-scotland-32635871|archive-date=21 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2016 Scottish Parliament election|2016 Scottish election]], the SNP lost a net total of 6 seats, losing its overall majority in the Scottish Parliament, but returning for a third consecutive term as a minority government despite gaining an additional 1.1% of the constituency vote, for the party's best ever result, from the 2011 election however 2.3% of the regional list vote. On the constituency vote, the SNP gained 11 seats from Labour, but lost the [[Edinburgh Southern (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Edinburgh Southern]] constituency to the party. The Conservatives and Liberal Democrats each gained two constituency seats from the SNP on 2011 ([[Aberdeenshire West (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Aberdeenshire West]] and [[Edinburgh Central (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Edinburgh Central]] for the Conservatives and [[Edinburgh Western (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Edinburgh Western]] and [[North East Fife (Scottish Parliament constituency)|North East Fife]] for the Liberal Democrats).\n\nThis election was followed by the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 European Union referendum]] after which the SNP joined with the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] and [[Scottish Greens|Greens]] to call for continued membership of the EU. Despite a consequential increase in the Conservative vote at the [[2017 Scottish local elections|2017 local elections]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Association|first=Press|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/may/06/local-elections-sturgeon-plays-down-tory-success-in-scotland|title=Local elections: Sturgeon plays down Tory success in Scotland|date=2017-05-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> the SNP for the first time became the largest party in each of Scotland's four city councils: [[2017 Aberdeen City Council election|Aberdeen]], [[2017 Dundee City Council election|Dundee]], [[2017 City of Edinburgh Council election|Edinburgh]] and [[2017 Glasgow City Council election|Glasgow]], where a Labour administration was ousted after 37 years<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-loses-glasgow-city-council-local-elections-2017-snp-scotland-brexit-general-a7719446.html|title=Labour loses control of Glasgow City Council for the first time in 40 years|date=2017-05-05|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>.\n\nAt the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 UK general election]] the SNP underperformed compared to polling expectations, losing 21 seats to bring their number of Westminster MPs down to 35 - however this was still the party's third best result ever.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Johnson|first1=Simon|last2=Henderson|first2=Barney|title=Scotland election results: Alex Salmond defeated and SNP suffer huge losses as Tory chances boosted north of the border|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/06/08/scotland-election-results-live-will-snp-nicola-sturgeon-do/|website=Telegraph|accessdate=9 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609041756/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/06/08/scotland-election-results-live-will-snp-nicola-sturgeon-do/|archive-date=9 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=General election 2017: SNP lose a third of seats amid Tory surge|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-40192707|website=BBC News|accessdate=9 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609030212/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-40192707|archive-date=9 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Thomas|first1=Natalie|last2=Dickie|first2=Mure|title=Scottish election results strike blow to SNP plans for IndyRef2|url=https://www.ft.com/content/3bc5642e-4c96-11e7-919a-1e14ce4af89b|website=Financial Times|access-date=9 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170611053343/https://www.ft.com/content/3bc5642e-4c96-11e7-919a-1e14ce4af89b|archive-date=11 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> This was largely attributed by many, including former Deputy First Minister John Swinney,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-40192707|title=General election 2017: SNP lose a third of seats amid Tory surge|last=|first=|date=9 June 2017|website=BBC|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024045322/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-40192707|archive-date=24 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> to their stance on holding a [[proposed second Scottish independence referendum|second Scottish independence referendum]] and saw a swing to the Unionist parties, with seats being picked up by the Conservatives, Labour and the Liberal Democrats and a reduction in their majorities in the other seats. [[Stephen Gethins]], MP for [[North East Fife (UK Parliament constituency)|North East Fife]], came out of this election with a majority of just 2 to the Liberal Democrat candidate. High-profile losses included SNP Commons leader [[Angus Robertson]] in [[Moray (UK Parliament constituency)|Moray]] and former party leader and First Minister [[Alex Salmond]] in [[Gordon (UK Parliament constituency)|Gordon]].\n\nThe SNP went on to achieve its best ever [[European Parliament]] result [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|in the final election]] before [[Brexit]], the party taking its [[Member of European Parliament|MEP]] total to 3 or half of [[Scotland (European Parliament constituency)|Scottish seats]]. Later that year the SNP experienced a surge in the [[United Kingdom general election, 2019|2019 general election]], winning 45.0% of the vote and 47 seats, its second best result ever. Although the party suffered a loss to the Liberal Democrats, it gained the seat of its then UK leader [[Jo Swinson]], along with 7 from the Conservatives and 6 from Labour. This victory was generally attributed to Sturgeon's cautious approach regarding holding a second independence referendum and strong emphasis on EU membership during the election<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2019-50766014|title=SNP wins election landslide in Scotland|date=2019-12-13|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-GB}}</ref>. \n\n==Constitution and structure==\nThe local Branches are the primary level of organisation in the SNP. All of the Branches within each Scottish Parliament constituency form a Constituency Association, which coordinates the work of the Branches within the constituency, coordinates the activities of the party in the constituency, and acts as a point of liaison between an MSP or MP and the party. Constituency Associations are composed of delegates from all of the Branches within the constituency.\n\nThe annual National Conference is the supreme governing body of the SNP, and is responsible for determining party policy and electing the National Executive Committee. The National Conference is composed of:\n* delegates from every Branch and Constituency Association\n* the members of the National Executive Committee\n* 15 members elected by the National Conference\n* every SNP MSP, MP and MEP\n* a number of SNP local councillors, and\n* delegates from one of the SNP's Affiliated Organisations ([[Young Scots for Independence]], [[SNP Students]], [[SNP Trade Union Group]] and the Association of Nationalist Councillors)\n\nThe National Council serves as the SNP's governing body between National Conferences, and its decisions are binding, unless rescinded or modified by the National Conference. There are also regular meetings of the National Assembly, which provides a forum for detailed discussion of party policy by party members.\n\nThe party has an active youth wing, the [[Young Scots for Independence]], as well as a student wing, the [[Federation of Student Nationalists]]. There is also an [[SNP Trade Union Group]]. There is an independently owned monthly newspaper, ''[[The Scots Independent]]'', which is highly supportive of the party.\n\nThe SNP's leadership is vested in its National Executive Committee (NEC), which is made up of the party's elected office bearers and six elected members (voted for at conference). The SNP parliamentarians (Holyrood and Westminster) and councillors have representation on the NEC, as do the Trade Union Group, the youth wing and the student wing.\n\n===National Executive Committee===\nThe National Executive Committee is composed of:\n* President: [[Ian Hudghton]]\n* Leader: [[Nicola Sturgeon]] [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|MSP]] <small>([[Glasgow Southside (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Glasgow Southside]])</small>\n* Depute Leader: [[Keith Brown (Scottish politician)|Keith Brown]] [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|MSP]] <small>([[Clackmannanshire and Dunblane (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Clackmannanshire and Dunblane]])</small>\n* National Treasurer: [[Colin Beattie]] [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|MSP]] <small>([[Midlothian North and Musselburgh (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Midlothian North and Musselburgh]])</small>\n* National Secretary: Dr Angus MacLeod\n* Business Convener: [[Kirsten Oswald]] [[Member of parliament|MP]] <small>([[East Renfrewshire (UK Parliament constituency)|East Renfrewshire]])</small>\n* Organisation Convener: Stacy Bradley\n* Member Support Convener: John Clark \n* Policy Development Convener: [[Alyn Smith]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]] <small>([[Stirling (UK Parliament constituency)|Stirling]])</small>\n* Local Government Convener: Councillor Ellen Forson <small>([[Clackmannanshire South]])</small>\n* Women's Convener: Councillor Rhiannon Spear <small>([[Greater Pollok (ward)|Greater Pollok]])</small>\n* Equalities Convener: Fiona Robertson\n* Black, Asian and Minority Ethnic Convener: Councillor Graham Campbell <small>([[Springburn/Robroyston (ward)|Springburn/Robroyston]])</small>\n* Disabled Members' Convener: Morag Fulton\n* [[Tommy Sheppard]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]] <small>([[Edinburgh East (UK Parliament constituency)|Edinburgh East]])</small>\n* [[Alison Thewliss]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]] <small>([[Glasgow Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Glasgow Central]])</small>\n* Sixteen regional representatives\n* Representatives from the Association of Nationalist Councillors and affiliated organisations\n\n===Membership===\nSince 18 September 2014 (the day of the Scottish independence referendum), party membership has more than quadrupled (from 25,642), surpassing the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] and, briefly, [[Conservatives (UK)|Conservatives]] to become the second-largest political party in the United Kingdom in terms of membership.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/theSNP/status/1036557191648604160//|title=New figures show our party is now powered by 125,482 members - making @theSNP the second biggest party in the UK.|access-date=3 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190524143611/https://twitter.com/theSNP/status/1036557191648604160|archive-date=24 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> As of August 2018, the Party has 125,482 members.\n\n===European affiliation===\nThe SNP retains close links with [[Plaid Cymru]], its counterpart in [[Wales]]. [[UK MPs|MPs]] from both parties co-operate closely with each other and work as a single parliamentary group within the House of Commons. Both the SNP and Plaid Cymru are members of the [[European Free Alliance]] (EFA), a European political party comprising [[regionalism (politics)|regionalist]] political parties. The EFA co-operates with the larger [[European Green Party]] to form [[The Greens\u2013European Free Alliance]] (Greens/EFA) group in the [[European Parliament]].\n\nPrior to its affiliation with The Greens\u2013European Free Alliance, the SNP had previously been allied with the [[European Progressive Democrats]] (1979\u20131984), [[Rainbow Group (1989\u20131994)|Rainbow Group]] (1989\u20131994) and [[European Radical Alliance]] (1994\u20131999).\n\nAs the UK is no longer a member of the EU, the SNP has no MEPs.\n\n==Party ideology==\n\n===Historical ideology===\nThe Scottish National Party did not have a clear ideological position until the 1970s, when it sought to explicitly present itself as a social democratic party in terms of party policy and publicity.<ref name=\"Lynch\">{{cite book|author=Peter Lynch|title=SNP: The History of the Scottish National Party|year=2002|publisher= Welsh Academic Press|page= }}</ref><ref name=\"Brand1978\">{{cite book|title=The National Movement in Scotland|publisher=Routledge and Kegan Paul|year=1978|pages=216\u201317|author=Jack Brand}}</ref> During the period from its foundation until the 1960s, the SNP was essentially a moderate [[centrism|centrist]] party.<ref name=\"Lynch\"/> Debate within the party focused more on the SNP being distinct as an all-Scotland national movement, with it being neither of the [[Left-wing politics|left]] nor the [[Right-wing politics|right]], but constituting a new politics that sought to put Scotland first.<ref name=\"Brand1978\"/><ref name=\"Brand199028\">{{cite book|title=\u2018Scotland\u2019, in Watson, Michael (ed.), Contemporary Minority Nationalism|publisher=Routledge|year=1990|page=28|author=Jack Brand}}</ref>\n\nThe SNP was formed through the merger of the centre-left [[National Party of Scotland|National Party of Scotland (NPS)]] and the centre-right [[Scottish Party]].<ref name=\"Brand1978\"/> The SNP's founders were united over [[self-determination]] in principle, though not its exact nature, or the best strategic means to achieve self-government. From the mid-1940s onwards, SNP policy was [[Political radicalism|radical]] and [[Redistribution of income and wealth|redistributionist]] in relation to land and in favour of \u2018the diffusion of economic power\u2019, including the [[decentralisation]] of industries such as coal to include the involvement of local authorities and regional planning bodies to control industrial structure and development.<ref name=\"Lynch\"/> Party policies supported the economic and social policy status quo of the post-war [[Welfare state in the United Kingdom|welfare state]].<ref name=\"Lynch\"/><ref name=\"Hassan2009120\">{{cite book|author=Gerry Hassan|title=The Modern SNP: From Protest to Power|year=2009|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|page=120}}</ref>\n\nBy the 1960s, the SNP was starting to become defined ideologically, with a social democratic tradition emerging as the party grew in urban, industrial Scotland, and its membership experienced an influx of social democrats from the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], the [[trade union]]s and the [[Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament]].<ref name=\"Brand199032\">{{cite book|title=\u2018Scotland\u2019, in Watson, Michael (ed.), Contemporary Minority Nationalism|publisher=Routledge|year=1990|page=32|author=Jack Brand}}</ref><ref name=\"Mitchell1996208\">{{cite book|author=James Mitchell|title=Strategies for Self-government: The Campaigns for a Scottish Parliament|year=1996|publisher=Polygon|page=208}}</ref> The emergence of [[William Wolfe|Billy Wolfe]] as a leading figure in the SNP also contributed to the leftwards shift. By this period, the Labour Party were also the dominant party in Scotland, in terms of electoral support and representation. Targeting Labour through emphasising left-of-centre policies and values was therefore electorally logical for the SNP, as well as tying in with the ideological preferences of many new party members.<ref name=\"Mitchell1996208\"/> In 1961, the SNP conference expressed the party's opposition to the siting of the [[United States|US]] [[UGM-27 Polaris|Polaris]] submarine base at the [[Holy Loch]]. This policy was followed in 1963 by a motion opposed to [[nuclear weapon]]s: a policy that has remained in place ever since.<ref name=\"Mitchell19961994\">{{cite book|author=James Mitchell|title=Strategies for Self-government: The Campaigns for a Scottish Parliament|year=1996|publisher=Polygon|page=194}}</ref> The 1964 policy document, ''SNP & You'', contained a clear centre-left policy platform, including commitments to [[full employment]], government intervention in fuel, power and transport, a state bank to guide economic development, encouragement of [[cooperative]]s and [[credit union]]s, extensive building of [[council house]]s (social housing) by central and local government, pensions adjusted to cost of living, a [[minimum wage]] and an improved [[NHS Scotland|national health service]].<ref name=\"Lynch\"/>\n\nThe 1960s also saw the beginnings of the SNP's efforts to establish an industrial organisation and mobilise amongst trade unionists in Scotland, with the establishment of the SNP Trade Union Group, and identifying the SNP with industrial campaigns, such as the [[Upper-Clyde Shipbuilders Work-in]] and the attempt of the workers at the Scottish ''[[Daily Express]]'' to run as a co-operative.<ref name=\"Lynch\"/> For the party manifestos for the two 1974 general elections, the SNP finally self-identified as a social democratic party, and proposed a range of social democratic policies.<ref name=\"Brand199027\">{{cite book|title=\u2018Scotland\u2019, in Watson, Michael (ed.), Contemporary Minority Nationalism|publisher=Routledge|year=1990|page=27|author=Jack Brand}}</ref><ref name=\"Hassan2009121\">{{cite book|author=Gerry Hassan|title=The Modern SNP: From Protest to Power|year=2009|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|page=121}}</ref> There was also an unsuccessful proposal at the 1975 party conference to rename the party as the ''Scottish National Party (Social Democrats)''.<ref name=\"Hepburn2013143\">{{cite book|author=Eve Hepburn|title=New Challenges for Stateless Nationalist and Regionalist Parties|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dTOOAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA143|date=18 October 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-96596-1|page=143|access-date=25 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503092815/https://books.google.com/books?id=dTOOAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA143|archive-date=3 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In the UK wide referendum on Britain\u2019s membership of the European Economic Community (EEC) in the same year as the aforementioned attempted name change, the SNP campaigned for Britain to leave the EEC.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Devenney|first=Andrew D.|date=2008|title=Regional Resistance to European Integration: The Case of the Scottish National Party, 1961-1972|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/20762312|journal=Historical Social Research / Historische Sozialforschung|volume=33|issue=3 (125)|pages=319\u2013345|issn=0172-6404}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-37107148|title=The dilemma facing Scotland's Eurosceptic nationalists|last=Ley|first=Shaun|date=2016-08-18|access-date=2020-01-12|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThere were further ideological and internal struggles after 1979, with the [[79 Group]] attempting to move the SNP further to the left, away from being what could be described a \"social-democratic\" party, to an expressly \"[[socialism|socialist]]\" party. Members of the 79 Group - including future party leader and [[First Minister of Scotland|First Minister]] [[Alex Salmond]] - were expelled from the party. This produced a response in the shape of the [[Campaign for Nationalism in Scotland]] from those who wanted the SNP to remain a \"broad church\", apart from arguments of left vs. right. The 1980s saw the SNP further define itself as a party of the political left, such as campaigning against the introduction of the [[community charge|poll tax]] in Scotland in 1989; one year before the tax was imposed on the rest of the UK.<ref name=\"Lynch\"/>\n\nIdeological tensions inside the SNP are further complicated by arguments between the so-called [[SNP gradualist]]s and [[SNP fundamentalist]]s. In essence, gradualists seek to advance Scotland to independence through further devolution, in a \"step-by-step\" strategy. They tend to be in the moderate left grouping, though much of the [[79 Group]] was gradualist in approach. However, this 79 Group gradualism was as much a reaction against the fundamentalists of the day, many of whom believed the SNP should not take a clear left or right position.<ref name=\"Lynch\"/>\n\n===Current ideology===\nThe SNP's policy base is mostly in the mainstream Western European [[social democracy|social democratic]] tradition. Among its policies are commitments to [[Transgender rights in the United Kingdom|gender self-identification]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2019/09/03/scottish-government-public-consultation-gender-recognition-act/|title=The Scottish government just confirmed the next step for the reformation of the Gender Recognition Act|date=2019-09-03|website=PinkNews - Gay news, reviews and comment from the world's most read lesbian, gay, bisexual, and trans news service|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>, reducing the voting age to sixteen years, [[unilateral nuclear disarmament]], [[progressive tax|progressive personal taxation]], the eradication of poverty; the building of affordable [[social housing]], government-subsidised [[Higher education in Scotland|higher education]], [[proportional representation]], and a pay increase for nurses.<ref>{{cite web|title=Re-elect a Scottish Government working for Scotland. Scottish National Party Manifesto|url= http://www.votesnp.com/campaigns/SNP_Manifesto_2011_lowRes.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=Scottish National Party |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110418171842/http://www.votesnp.com/campaigns/SNP_Manifesto_2011_lowRes.pdf |archivedate=18 April 2011|accessdate=2 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Cut to APD vital for Scotland's future success|url=http://www.snp.org/media-centre/news/2014/jun/cut-apd-vital-scotlands-future-success|publisher=Scottish National Party|accessdate=6 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141209052937/http://www.snp.org/media-centre/news/2014/jun/cut-apd-vital-scotlands-future-success|archivedate=9 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe SNP is against the renewal of [[Trident nuclear programme|Trident]] and wants to continue providing free university education in Scotland.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2015-scotland-32380783 |title=Election 2015: Scottish National Party manifesto at-a-glance |access-date=21 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180126134923/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2015-scotland-32380783 |archive-date=26 January 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe SNP would like to see an [[Scottish independence|independent Scotland]] as a member of the [[European Union]] and [[NATO]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/oct/29/nicola-sturgeon-scottish-veto-eu-referendum|title=Nicola Sturgeon calls for Scottish veto on EU referendum|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=29 October 2014|access-date=16 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170403112341/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/oct/29/nicola-sturgeon-scottish-veto-eu-referendum|archive-date=3 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and has left open the prospect of an independent Scotland joining the [[Euro|Euro.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/politics/an-independent-scotland-in-europe-brexit-snp-conference-nicola-sturgeon|title=An independent Scotland in Europe?|last=Hughes|first=Kirsty|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>  The party also supports the expansion of the membership of these intergovernmental bodies to areas such as the [[Western Balkans]] and [[Ukraine]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.scot/news/17860080.snp-mp-stewart-mcdonald-wins-highest-state-order-ukraine/|title=SNP MP Stewart McDonald wins highest state order from Ukraine|website=The National|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/02/18/scotland-independence-russia-putin-ukraine-propaganda/|title=How Russia Is Prodding Scotland Toward Independence|last=Leask|first=David|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>.\n\nIt has been noted that the party contains a broader spectrum of opinion regarding economic issues than most political parties in the UK due to its status as \"the only viable vehicle for Scottish independence\",<ref name=splits>{{cite web |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/staggers/2017/03/5-biggest-splits-behind-snps-disciplined-facade |title=5 of the biggest splits behind the SNP's disciplined facade |last=Millar |first=James |date=16 March 2017 |website=[[New Statesman]] |access-date=8 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408171758/http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/staggers/2017/03/5-biggest-splits-behind-snps-disciplined-facade |archive-date=8 April 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> with the party's parliamentary group at Westminster consisting of socialists such as [[Tommy Sheppard]] and [[Mhairi Black]] as well as supporters of tax cuts like [[Stewart Hosie]] and, previously, former Conservative [[Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh]].<ref name=splits /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/staggers/2016/10/snp-cant-mask-its-left-right-split-forever |title=The SNP can't mask its left-right split forever |last=Millar |first=James |date=13 October 2016 |website=[[New Statesman]] |access-date=8 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408171658/http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/staggers/2016/10/snp-cant-mask-its-left-right-split-forever |archive-date=8 April 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAt the 2017 SNP Conference, on 10 October, Nicola Sturgeon made several commitments,<ref>[https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/thesnp/pages/3923/attachments/original/1507283291/10_06_SNP_83rd_Conference_A5_low-res.pdf?1507283291]  {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010211403/https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/thesnp/pages/3923/attachments/original/1507283291/10_06_SNP_83rd_Conference_A5_low-res.pdf?1507283291 |date=10 October 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/15587446.Nicola_Sturgeon__Scottish_people_still__trust_SNP_to_deliver_/|title=Nicola Sturgeon: Scottish people still 'trust SNP to deliver'|website=HeraldScotland|accessdate=21 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621221332/http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/15587446.Nicola_Sturgeon__Scottish_people_still__trust_SNP_to_deliver_/|archive-date=21 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> including:\n* Completion of the largest floating wind-power facility in the world, at [[Peterhead]].\n* Council Tax exemption for those leaving care homes.\n* Denuclearisation efforts, particularly the ban on \"weapons of mass destruction\".\n* Free sanitary products for all students.\n* Creating a not-for-profit oil company for Scotland.\n* Covering the application fee for EU nationals employed in the Scottish public sector.\n* Opposition to \"austerity\" measures imposed from abroad.\n* Opposition to any attempt at privatisation of the NHS.\n\nDespite being staunchly pro-EU, Sturgeon has also condemned the EU for failing to act to protect the rights of EU citizens in [[Catalonia]], following the use of violence after [[2017 Catalan independence referendum]], condemning  the later arrests of pro-independence Catalan ministers without endorsing their [[Catalan declaration of independence|unilateral declaration of independence]].<ref>{{cite tweet|last=Sturgeon |first=Nicola |author-link=Nicola Sturgeon |user=NicolaSturgeon |number=914434540000727040 |date=1 October 2017 |title=Increasingly concerned by images from #Catalonia. Regardless of views on independence, we should all condemn the scenes being witnessed and call on Spain to change course before someone is seriously hurt. Let people vote peacefully. |access-date=3 November 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|last=Sturgeon |first=Nicola |user=NicolaSturgeon |number=926121808658616320 |date=2 November 2017 |title=Regardless of opinion on Catalonia, the jailing of elected leaders is wrong and should be condemned by all democrats |access-date=3 November 2017 |link=no }}</ref>\n\n==Leadership==\n\n===Leader of the Scottish National Party===\n[[File:First Minister, Nicola Sturgeon.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Nicola Sturgeon]], Leader of the Scottish National Party]]\n* [[Alexander MacEwen|Sir Alexander MacEwen]], 1934\u20131936\n* [[Andrew Dewar Gibb]], 1936\u20131940\n* [[William Power (Scottish politician)|William Power]], 1940\u20131942\n* [[Douglas Young (classicist)|Douglas Young]], 1942\u20131945\n* [[Bruce Watson (politician)|Bruce Watson]], 1945\u20131947\n* [[Robert McIntyre]], 1947\u20131956\n* [[Jimmy Halliday|James Halliday]], 1956\u20131960\n* [[Arthur Donaldson]], 1960\u20131969\n* [[William Wolfe]], 1969\u20131979\n* [[Gordon Wilson (Scottish politician)|Gordon Wilson]], 1979\u20131990\n* [[Alex Salmond]], 1990\u20132000\n* [[John Swinney]], 2000\u20132004\n* [[Alex Salmond]], 2004\u20132014\n* [[Nicola Sturgeon]], 2014\u2013present\n\n===Depute Leader of the Scottish National Party=== <!--Note: Depute is not a spelling error. That is how the party officially spells his/her post and is part of the Scots language.-->\n* [[Sandy Milne]], 1964\u20131966\n* [[William Wolfe]], 1966\u20131969\n* [[George Leslie (politician)|George Leslie]], 1969\u20131971\n* [[Douglas Henderson (SNP politician)|Douglas Henderson]], 1971\u20131973\n* [[Gordon Wilson (Scottish politician)|Gordon Wilson]], 1973\u20131974\n* [[Margo MacDonald]], 1974\u20131979\n* [[Douglas Henderson (SNP politician)|Douglas Henderson]], 1979\u20131981\n* [[Jim Fairlie]], 1981\u20131984\n* [[Margaret Ewing]], 1984\u20131987\n* [[Alex Salmond]], 1987\u20131990\n* [[Alasdair Morgan]], 1990\u20131991\n* [[Jim Sillars]], 1991\u20131992\n* [[Allan Macartney]], 1992\u20131998\n* [[John Swinney]], 1998\u20132000\n* [[Roseanna Cunningham]], 2000\u20132004\n* [[Nicola Sturgeon]], 2004\u20132014\n* [[Stewart Hosie]], 2014\u20132016\n* [[Angus Robertson]], 2016\u20132018<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-37640935|title=Angus Robertson named as SNP deputy leader|date=2018-10-13|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-12-05|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821112444/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-37640935|archive-date=21 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-42931413|title=Robertson quits as SNP deputy leader|date=2018-02-03|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-02-03|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623114505/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-42931413|archive-date=23 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Keith Brown (Scottish politician)|Keith Brown]], 2018\u2013present<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-44397652|title=SNP conference: Keith Brown elected deputy leader|date=2018-06-08|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-12-05|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111200539/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-44397652|archive-date=11 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===President of the Scottish National Party===\n* [[James Graham, 6th Duke of Montrose]] and [[Robert Bontine Cunninghame Graham]] (joint), 1934\u20131936 \n* [[Roland Muirhead]], 1936\u20131950\n* [[Tom Gibson (Scottish politician)|Tom Gibson]], 1950\u20131958\n* [[Robert McIntyre]], 1958\u20131980\n* [[William Wolfe]], 1980\u20131982\n* [[Donald Stewart (Scottish politician)|Donald Stewart]], 1982\u20131987\n* [[Winnie Ewing]], 1987\u20132005\n* [[Ian Hudghton]], 2005\u2013present\n\n===National Secretary of the Scottish National Party===\n* [[John MacCormick]], 1934\u20131942\n* [[Robert McIntyre]], 1942\u20131947\n* [[Mary Fraser Dott]], 1947\u20131951\n* [[Robert Curran (Scottish politician)|Robert Curran]], 1951\u20131954\n* John Smart, 1954\u20131963\n* Malcolm Shaw, 1963\u20131964\n* [[Gordon Wilson (Scottish politician)|Gordon Wilson]], 1964\u20131971\n* [[Muriel Gibson (SNP)|Muriel Gibson]], 1971\u20131972\n* [[Rosemary Hall (political activist)|Rosemary Hall]], 1972\u20131975\n* [[Muriel Gibson (SNP)|Muriel Gibson]], 1975\u20131977\n* Chrissie MacWhirter, 1977\u20131979\n* Iain Murray, 1979\u20131981\n* [[Neil MacCallum]], 1981\u20131986\n* [[John Swinney]], 1986\u20131992\n* [[Alasdair Morgan]], 1992\u20131997\n* [[Stewart Hosie]], 1999\u20132003\n* [[Alasdair Allan]], 2003\u20132006\n* [[Duncan Ross (Scottish politician)|Duncan Ross]], 2006\u20132012\n* [[Patrick Grady]], 2012\u20132016\n* Dr Angus MacLeod, 2016\u2013present\n\n===Leader of the parliamentary party, Scottish Parliament===\n* [[Alex Salmond]] <small>([[Banff and Buchan (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Banff and Buchan]]),</small> 1999\u20132000 \n* [[John Swinney]] <small>([[North Tayside (Scottish Parliament constituency)|North Tayside]]),</small> 2000\u20132004\n* [[Nicola Sturgeon]] <small>([[Glasgow (Scottish Parliament electoral region)|Glasgow]]),</small> 2004\u20132007\n* [[Alex Salmond]] <small>([[Aberdeenshire East (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Aberdeenshire East]]),</small> 2007\u20132014\n* [[Nicola Sturgeon]] <small>([[Glasgow Southside (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Glasgow Southside]])</small> 2014\u2013present\n\n===Leader of the parliamentary party, House of Commons===\n* [[Donald Stewart (Scottish politician)|Donald Stewart]] <small>([[Na h-Eileanan an Iar (UK Parliament constituency)|Western Isles]]),</small> 1974\u20131987\n* [[Margaret Ewing]] <small>([[Moray (UK Parliament constituency)|Moray]]),</small> 1987\u20131999\n* [[Alasdair Morgan]] <small>([[Galloway and Upper Nithsdale (UK Parliament constituency)|Galloway and Upper Nithsdale]]),</small> 1999\u20132001\n* [[Alex Salmond]] <small>([[Banff and Buchan (UK Parliament constituency)|Banff and Buchan]]),</small> 2001\u20132007\n* [[Angus Robertson]] <small>([[Moray (UK Parliament constituency)|Moray]]),</small> 2007\u20132017\n* [[Ian Blackford]] <small>([[Ross, Skye and Lochaber (UK Parliament constituency)|Ross, Skye and Lochaber]]),</small> 2017\u2013present\n\n=== Chief Executive Officer ===\n\n* [[Michael Russell (politician)|Michael Russell]], 1994\u20131999\n* [[Peter Murrell]], 2007\u2013present\n\n==Government Ministers and Shadow Cabinet==\n\n===Scottish Parliament===\n{{see also|Government of the 5th Scottish Parliament|Scottish Government|Members of the 5th Scottish Parliament}} \n\n{{As of|February 2019}}, the Cabinet of the Scottish Government is as follows:\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"font-size:97%\"\n|-\n! colspan= 3 | Cabinet Secretaries <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.gov.scot/news/new-cabinet-appointed|title=New Cabinet appointed|website=Scottish Government News|language=en|access-date=2018-06-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627062247/https://news.gov.scot/news/new-cabinet-appointed|archive-date=27 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! Portfolio\n! Minister\n!! class=\"unsortable\" | Image\n\n|-\n| '''[[First Minister of Scotland|First Minister]]'''\n| data-sort-value=\"Sturgeon\" | {{small|[[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|The Right Hon.]]}} [[Nicola Sturgeon]] {{small|[[Member of the Scottish Parliament|MSP]]}}\n<small>([[Glasgow Southside (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Glasgow Southside]])</small>\n| [[File:Nicola Sturgeon election infobox.jpg|85px]]\n|-\n| '''[[Deputy First Minister of Scotland|Deputy First Minister]]'''<br />[[Cabinet Secretary for Education and Skills]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Swinney\" | [[John Swinney]] {{small|MSP}}\n<small>([[Perthshire North (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Perthshire North]])</small>\n| [[File:John Swinney, Deputy First Minister.png|85px]]\n|-\n|[[Cabinet Secretary for Justice]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Yousaf\" | [[Humza Yousaf]] {{small|MSP}}\n<small>([[Glasgow Pollok (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Glasgow Pollok]])</small>\n| [[File:HumzaYousafMSP20110507.JPG|85px]]\n|-\n| [[Cabinet Secretary for Health and Sport]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Freeman\" | [[Jeane Freeman]] {{small|[[Officer of the Order of the British Empire|OBE]] MSP}}\n<small>([[Carrick, Cumnock and Doon Valley (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Carrick, Cumnock and Doon Valley]])</small>\n| [[File:JeaneFreemanMSP.jpg|85px]]\n|-\n|[[Cabinet Secretary for Finance, Economy and Fair Work|Cabinet Secretary for Finance]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Vacant\" |[[Kate Forbes]] <small>MSP</small>\n<small>([[Skye, Lochaber and Badenoch (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Skye, Lochaber and Badenoch]])</small>\n|[[File:KateForbesMSP-May2016.jpg|frameless|100x100px]]\n|-\n|[[Cabinet Secretary for Environment, Climate Change and Land Reform]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Cunningham\" |[[Roseanna Cunningham]] {{small|MSP}}\n<small>([[Perthshire South and Kinross-shire (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Perthshire South and Kinross-shire]])</small>\n|[[File:Cabinet Secretary for the Environment, Climate Change and Land Reform, Roseanna Cunningham.png|85px]]\n|-\n|[[Cabinet Secretary for Rural Economy|Cabinet Secretary for Rural Economy and Tourism]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Ewing\" |[[Fergus Ewing]] {{small|MSP}}\n<small>([[Inverness and Nairn (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Inverness and Nairn]])</small>\n|[[File:Cabinet Secretary for the Rural Economy and Connectivity, Fergus Ewing.png|85px]]\n|-\n|[[Cabinet Secretary for Government Business and Constitutional Relations|Cabinet Secretary for the Constitution, Europe and External Affairs]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Russell\" | [[Michael Russell (politician)|Michael Russell]] {{small|MSP}}\n<small>([[Argyll and Bute (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Argyll and Bute]])</small>\n| [[File:Michael_Russell,_Cabinet_Secretary_for_Education_%26_Lifelong_Learning_(2).jpg|85px]]\n|-\n|[[Cabinet Secretary for Communities and Local Government]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Campbell\" | [[Aileen Campbell]] {{small|MSP}}\n<small>([[Clydesdale (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Clydesdale]])</small>\n| [[File:Aileen Campbell.jpg|85px]]\n|-\n|[[Cabinet Secretary for Culture, Tourism and External Affairs|Cabinet Secretary for Economy, Fair Work and Culture]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Hyslop\" |[[Fiona Hyslop]] {{small|MSP}}\n<small>([[Linlithgow (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Linlithgow]])</small>\n|[[File:Cabinet Secretary for Culture, Tourism and External Affairs, Fiona Hyslop.png|85px]]\n|-\n|[[Cabinet Secretary for Transport, Infrastructure and Connectivity]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Matheson\" |[[Michael Matheson (politician)|Michael Matheson]] {{small|MSP}}\n<small>([[Falkirk West (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Falkirk West]])</small>\n|[[File:Cabinet Secretary for Justice, Michael Matheson.png|85px]]\n|-\n|[[Cabinet Secretary for Social Security and Older People]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Somerville\" | [[Shirley-Anne Somerville]] {{small|MSP}}\n<small>([[Dunfermline (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Dunfermline]])</small>\n| [[File:Minister for Further Education, Higher Education and Science, Shirley Anne Sommerville.png|85px]]\n|-\n|}\n\n===House of Commons ===\nAs of January 2020, the Shadow Cabinet of the SNP in Westminster was as follows.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/mps-lords-and-offices/government-and-opposition1/scottish-national-party/|title=Scottish National Party Spokespersons|website=UK Parliament|language=English|access-date=2019-07-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190524075054/https://www.parliament.uk/mps-lords-and-offices/government-and-opposition1/scottish-national-party/|archive-date=24 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"  style=\"font-size:97%\"\n|-\n! Portfolio  !! Shadow Secretary/Minister\n|-\n|'''Westminster Leader'''\n| [[Ian Blackford|Ian Blackford MP]]\n<small>([[Ross, Skye and Lochaber (UK Parliament constituency)|Ross, Skye and Lochaber]])</small>\n|-\n|'''Westminster Depute Leader'''\n| [[Kirsty Blackman|Kirsty Blackman MP]]\n<small>([[Aberdeen North (UK Parliament constituency)|Aberdeen North]])</small>\n|-\n| Shadow Chancellor\n| [[Alison Thewliss|Alison Thewliss MP]]\n<small>([[Glasgow Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Glasgow Central]])</small>\n|-\n| Shadow Foreign Secretary\n|[[Alyn Smith|Alyn Smith MP]]\n<small>([[Stirling (UK Parliament constituency)|Stirling]])</small>\n|-\n| Shadow Secretary of State for Health and Social Care <br> Shadow Secretary of State for Exiting the EU\n|[[Philippa Whitford|Dr Philippa Whitford MP]]\n<small>([[Central Ayr