|2|6|background-color=#DDDDDD|{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}}}|| SNP won a plurality within Scotland.\n|-\n| [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2019]]|| {{increase}} 37.8% ||{{Composition bar|3|6|background-color=#DDDDDD|{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}}}|| Last European election before [[Brexit]]. Best ever result for SNP in both seats and vote share.\n|}\n\n===Former District Councils===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year<ref name=\"The Scottish National Party\"/>\n ! Share of votes !! Seats won \n|-\n|[[1974 Scottish local elections|1974]]||12.4%||{{Composition bar|62|1158|background-color=#DDDDDD|{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n|[[1977 Scottish local elections|1977]]||24.2%||{{Composition bar|170|1158|background-color=#DDDDDD|{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n|[[1980 Scottish local elections|1980]]||15.5%||{{Composition bar|54|1158|background-color=#DDDDDD|{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n|[[1984 Scottish local elections|1984]]||11.7%||{{Composition bar|59|1158|background-color=#DDDDDD|{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n|[[1988 Scottish local elections|1988]]||21.3%||{{Composition bar|113|1158|background-color=#DDDDDD|{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n|[[1992 Scottish local elections|1992]]||24.3%||{{Composition bar|150|1158|background-color=#DDDDDD|{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}}}\n|}\n\n===Former Regional Councils===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year<ref name=\"The Scottish National Party\"/>\n ! Share of votes !! Seats won \n|-\n|[[1974 Scottish local elections|1974]]||12.6%||{{Composition bar|18|524|background-color=#DDDDDD|{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n|[[1978 Scottish regional elections|1978]]||20.9%||{{Composition bar|18|524|background-color=#DDDDDD|{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n|[[1982 Scottish regional elections|1982]]||13.4%||{{Composition bar|23|524|background-color=#DDDDDD|{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n|[[1986 Scottish regional elections|1986]]||18.2%||{{Composition bar|36|524|background-color=#DDDDDD|{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n|[[1990 Scottish regional elections|1990]]||21.8%||{{Composition bar|42|524|background-color=#DDDDDD|{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n|[[1994 Scottish regional elections|1994]]||26.8%||{{Composition bar|73|453|background-color=#DDDDDD|{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}}}\n|}\n\n== Fundamentalists and gradualists ==\n{{main|Fundamentalists and gradualists}}\nThe  viewpoint within the Scottish National Party is the idea that [[Scottish independence]] can be won by the accumulation by the [[Scottish Parliament]] of powers that the [[UK Parliament]] currently has over a protracted period of time. It is also a philosophy that emphasises the election of an SNP government should bring about trust in the Scottish people in the ability of [[Scotland]] to govern herself, thus bringing increased support for independence.\n\nGradualism stands in opposition to the so-called fundamentalist point of view, which believes that the SNP should emphasise independence more widely in order to achieve it. The argument goes that if the SNP is unprepared to argue for its central policy then it is unlikely ever to persuade the public of its worthiness.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/1999/may/06/uk.politicalnews1|title=SNP's radical wing threatens to split party|last=Seenan|first=By Gerard|date=1999-05-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-02|last2=MacAskill|first2=Ewen|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n=== Notable fundamentalists ===\n* [[Kenny MacAskill]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Margo MacDonald]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Alex Neil (politician)|Alex Neil]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Notable gradualists ===\n* [[Alex Salmond]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[John Swinney]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/in_depth/uk_politics/2000/conferences/snp/865888.stm|title=Tussle for the top |website= BBC News |date=21 September 2000 |access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Politics|United Kingdom|Scotland}}\n* [[Culture of Scotland]]\n* [[Politics of Scotland]]\n* [[History of Scottish devolution]]\n* [[It's Scotland's oil]]\n* [[Radio Free Scotland]]\n* [[Scottish Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament]]\n* [[The National (Scotland)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Brand, Jack, ''The National Movement in Scotland'', Routledge and Kegan Paul, 1978\n* Brand, Jack, \u2018Scotland\u2019, in Watson, Michael (ed.), ''Contemporary Minority Nationalism'', Routledge, 1990\n* [[Winnie Ewing]], [[Michael Russell (politician)|Michael Russell]], ''Stop the World; The Autobiography of Winnie Ewing'' [[Birlinn (publisher)|Birlinn]], 2004\n* [[Richard J. Finlay]], ''Independent and Free: Scottish Politics and the Origins of the Scottish National Party 1918\u20131945'', John Donald Publishers, 1994\n* Hanham, H.J., ''Scottish Nationalism'', [[Harvard University Press]], 1969\n* [[Christopher Harvie]], ''Scotland and Nationalism: Scottish Society and Politics 1707 to the Present'', Routledge (4th edition), 2004\n* [[Gerry Hassan]] (ed.), ''The Modern SNP: From Protest to Power'', [[Edinburgh University Press]], 2009, {{ISBN|0748639918}}\n* Lynch, Peter, ''SNP: The History of the Scottish National Party'', Welsh Academic Press, 2002\n* [[John MacCormick]], ''The Flag in the Wind: The Story of the National Movement in Scotland'', [[Victor Gollancz Ltd]], 1955\n* Mitchell, James, ''Strategies for Self-government: The Campaigns for a Scottish Parliament'', [[Birlinn (publisher)|Polygon]], 1996\n* Mitchell, James, Bennie, Lynn and Johns, Rob, ''The Scottish National Party: Transition to Power'', [[Oxford University Press]], 2011, {{ISBN|0199580006}}\n* Mitchell, James and Hassan, Gerry (eds), ''Scottish National Party Leaders'', Biteback, 2016. \n* [[Jim Sillars]], ''Scotland: the Case for Optimism'', Polygon, 1986\n* [[William Wolfe]], ''Scotland Lives: the Quest for Independence'', Reprographia, 1973\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links|n=Category:Scottish National Party|commons=Category:Scottish National Party|wikt=no|v=no|b=no|s=no|voy=no|q=no}}\n* [https://www.snp.org/ Scottish National Party] \u2013 Official website\n\n{{SNP}}\n{{SNP MSPs}}\n{{SNP MPs}}\n{{Former SNP MSPs}}\n{{Former SNP MPs}}\n{{SNP MEPs}}\n{{Political parties in Scotland}}\n{{Members of the European Free Alliance}}\n{{Political parties in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Nationalism in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:Scottish National Party| ]]\n[[Category:1934 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Advocates of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Constitution of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:European Free Alliance]]\n[[Category:Nationalist parties in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1934]]\n[[Category:Political parties in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Politics of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Scottish independence]]\n[[Category:Social democratic parties]]\n[[Category:Social democratic parties in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Anti-austerity political parties in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "RedGoldandBlue", "label": "safe", "comment": "minor formatting fixes in tables", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scottish_National_Party"}
{"title_page": "L'Auvergnat de Paris", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n'''''L'Auvergnat de Paris''''' is a [[France|French]] weekly newspaper started on {{start date|1882|07|14|df=y}} by Louis Bonnet, and, until 2009, distributed throughout France. It had a circulation of around {{formatnum:15000}}, falling in its last years to around {{formatnum:10000}} before going into [[administration (law)|administration]].<ref name=\"strategies\"/> It had the sub-title {{lang|fr|Du Massif central et fier de l\u2019\u00eatre}} (\"From the [[Massif Central]] and proud to be so\") and was a [[trade journal]] for Paris restaurants and brasseries. An Auvergnat is someone who comes from the [[Auvergne (province)|Auvergne province]] or [[Auvergne (region)|Auvergne region]] of France.\n\nIn July 2008 was bought by the ''[[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 \u00e0 responsabilit\u00e9 limit\u00e9e]]'' [[Bistrots et Comptoirs de Paris]] from businessman [[Gilles Barissat]], who had owned it for ten years.<ref name=\"strategies\">{{cite news|url=http://www.strategies.fr/actualites/medias/r97801W/l-auvergnat-de-paris-cherche-un-repreneur.html|title=L\u2019Auvergnat de Paris cherche un repreneur|language=fr|trans-title=''L'Auvergnat de Paris'' seeks buyer|date=27 May 2008|website=strategies.fr|accessdate=7 November 2015}}</ref> Facing severe financial difficulties, and having failed to find a new buyer, it was placed into [[liquidation]] on 6 October 2009 by the Paris Commercial Tribunal.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Le Figaro-\u00c9conomie|title=_|date=7 August 2009|language=fr}}</ref>\n\nGroupe [[Michel Burton Communication]] \u2013 publisher of ''[[Lettre CHR-CHD]]'', ''[[D\u00e9cision Boissons]]'', ''[[La Revue des Comptoirs]]'' and its supplements, ''[[Le Shaker]]'', ''[[Tendances]]'' and ''[[Carnets de bar]]'' \u2013 has owned the title since 15 October 2009. It returned to the newsstands on 5 November 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auvergnat.biz/acces-menu/articles/tous-les-articles/86-actualite/203-lauvergnat-de-paris-cest-reparti |title=L'Auvergnat de Paris c'est reparti |trans-title=''L'Auvergnat de Paris'' is relaunched |language=fr |website=auvergnat.biz |accessdate=7 November 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110906083428/http://www.auvergnat.biz/acces-menu/articles/tous-les-articles/86-actualite/203-lauvergnat-de-paris-cest-reparti |archivedate=September 6, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auvergnat.biz/acces-menu/articles/tous-les-articles/86-actualite/211-l-auvergnat-de-paris-est-de-retour |title=L\u2019Auvergnat de Paris est de retour |trans-title=''L'Auvergnat de Paris'' makes its comeback |language=fr |website=auvergnat.biz |accessdate=7 November 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110906090304/http://www.auvergnat.biz/acces-menu/articles/tous-les-articles/86-actualite/211-l-auvergnat-de-paris-est-de-retour |archivedate=September 6, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.auvergnat.com/ Official website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Auvergnat de Paris}}\n[[Category:1882 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:Newspapers published in Paris]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1882]]\n[[Category:Weekly newspapers published in France]]\n\n\n{{france-newspaper-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n'''''L'Auvergnat de Paris''''' is a [[France|French]] weekly newspaper started on {{start date|1882|07|14|df=y}} by Louis Bonnet, and, until 2009, distributed throughout France. It had a circulation of around {{formatnum:15000}}, falling in its last years to around {{formatnum:10000}} before going into [[administration (law)|administration]].<ref name=\"strategies\"/> It had the sub-title {{lang|fr|Du Massif central et fier de l\u2019\u00eatre}} (\"From the [[Massif Central]] and proud to be so\") and was a [[trade journal]] for Paris restaurants and brasseries. An Auvergnat is someone who comes from the [[Auvergne (province)|Auvergne province]] or [[Auvergne (region)|Auvergne region]] of France.\n\nIn July 2008 was bought by the ''[[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 \u00e0 responsabilit\u00e9 limit\u00e9e]]'' [[Bistrots et Comptoirs de Paris]] from businessman [[Gilles Barissat]], who had owned it for ten years.<ref name=\"strategies\">{{cite news|url=http://www.strategies.fr/actualites/medias/r97801W/l-auvergnat-de-paris-cherche-un-repreneur.html|title=L\u2019Auvergnat de Paris cherche un repreneur|language=fr|trans-title=''L'Auvergnat de Paris'' seeks buyer|date=27 May 2008|website=strategies.fr|accessdate=7 November 2015}}</ref> Facing severe financial difficulties, and having failed to find a new buyer, it was placed into [[liquidation]] on 6 October 2009 by the Paris Commercial Tribunal.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Le Figaro-\u00c9conomie|title=_|date=7 August 2009|language=fr}}</ref>\n\nGroupe [[Michel Burton Communication]] \u2013 publisher of ''[[Lettre CHR-CHD]]'', ''[[D\u00e9cision Boissons]]'', ''[[La Revue des Comptoirs]]'' and its supplements, ''[[Le Shaker]]'', ''[[Tendances]]'' and ''[[Carnets de bar]]'' \u2013 has owned the title since 15 October 2009. It returned to the newsstands on 5 November 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auvergnat.biz/acces-menu/articles/tous-les-articles/86-actualite/203-lauvergnat-de-paris-cest-reparti |title=L'Auvergnat de Paris c'est reparti |trans-title=''L'Auvergnat de Paris'' is relaunched |language=fr |website=auvergnat.biz |accessdate=7 November 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110906083428/http://www.auvergnat.biz/acces-menu/articles/tous-les-articles/86-actualite/203-lauvergnat-de-paris-cest-reparti |archivedate=September 6, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auvergnat.biz/acces-menu/articles/tous-les-articles/86-actualite/211-l-auvergnat-de-paris-est-de-retour |title=L\u2019Auvergnat de Paris est de retour |trans-title=''L'Auvergnat de Paris'' makes its comeback |language=fr |website=auvergnat.biz |accessdate=7 November 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110906090304/http://www.auvergnat.biz/acces-menu/articles/tous-les-articles/86-actualite/211-l-auvergnat-de-paris-est-de-retour |archivedate=September 6, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.auvergnat.com/ Official website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Auvergnat de Paris}}\n[[Category:1882 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:French-language newspapers]]\n[[Category:Newspapers published in Paris]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1882]]\n[[Category:Weekly newspapers published in France]]\n\n{{france-newspaper-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L%27Auvergnat_de_Paris"}
{"title_page": "Queen + Adam Lambert", "text_new": "{{short description|Queen's and Adam Lambert collaboration, in which Adam provides lead vocals for the band}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name           Jacob Mercury   = Queen + Adam Lambert\n| alias            = {{flatlist|\n* Q+AL\n* QAL\n}}\n| image            = AdamLambert-Queen 7-1-14 SJ.jpg\n| caption          = Queen + Adam Lambert in concert in [[San Jose, California|San Jose]] in 2014, L\u2013R: [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]], [[Adam Lambert]], [[Brian May]]\n| image_size       = 250px\n| landscape        = yes\n| background       = group_or_band\n| origin           = {{plainlist|\n* United Kingdom\n* United States\n}}\n| genre            = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| years_active     = 2011\u2013present\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = [[Queen (band)|Queen]], [[Queen + Paul Rodgers]], [[Adam Lambert]]\n| current_members  = * [[Brian May]]\n* [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]]\n* [[Adam Lambert]]\n*[[Spike Edney]]\n*Neil Fairclough\n*Tyler Warren\n| past_members     = *[[Rufus Tiger Taylor]]\n}}\n'''Queen + Adam Lambert''' (sometimes referred to as '''Q+AL''' or '''QAL''') is a collaboration between the active members of the British band [[Queen (band)|Queen]] ([[Brian May]] and [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]]) and American vocalist [[Adam Lambert]]. As with all other Queen performances since 1997, longstanding bassist [[John Deacon]] has declined to participate in the project due to his retirement. This is the first long-term collaboration of Queen since the [[Queen + Paul Rodgers]] project ended in 2009. Like the previous project, it was made clear that Lambert would not be replacing Queen frontman [[Freddie Mercury]], but rather that he would be featured with the band's active members. The collaboration originated when May and Taylor appeared on ''[[American Idol (season 8)|American Idol]]'' in 2009 when Lambert was a contestant. They began performing occasionally in 2011, conducted a short [[Queen + Adam Lambert Tour 2012|European tour]] in 2012, and in 2014 announced a world tour, the [[Queen + Adam Lambert Tour 2014\u20132015]] with dates in North America, Australia, New Zealand, Asia, Europe and South America. In the summer of 2016, the group performed several dates as part of a festival tour in Europe and several dates in Asia. The next year, the group announced a second worldwide tour scheduled for 2017 and 2018 and later announced a short United Kingdom tour for 2020.\n\nJoining May, Taylor and Lambert are long-time Queen touring keyboardist [[Spike Edney]], bassist Neil Fairclough and percussionist Tyler Warren. Although there are currently no plans to release a studio album with this lineup, May and Taylor have stated that there is a possibility of the group recording original material.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/queen-recording-adam-lambert/|title=Queen Hint at Recording New Material with Adam Lambert|work=Ultimate Classic Rock}}</ref>\n\n==Origin==\nQueen and Lambert first performed together in 2009 when Queen members Brian May and Roger Taylor appeared as guests on the [[American Idol (season 8)|eighth season of ''American Idol'']] on which Lambert was a contestant. On the show, Lambert and the eventual winner [[Kris Allen]] performed \"[[We Are the Champions]]\" together with the band.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1611896/kris-allen-adam-lambert-tear-up-queens-we-are-the-champions/|title=Kris Allen, Adam Lambert Tear Up Queen\u2019s \u2018We Are The Champions\u2019|date=20 May 2009|first=Gil|last=Kaufman|work=MTV News|accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref> Soon after the finale, May indicated to ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' that he was considering Lambert as a frontman for Queen.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/exclusive-queens-brian-may-addresses-adam-lambert-rumors-20090522 |title= Exclusive: Queen's Brian May Addresses Adam Lambert Rumors |author=Brian Hiatt |date=22 May 2009 |work=Rolling Stone }}</ref> May later revealed that he became interested in Lambert as a replacement for [[Paul Rodgers]] after watching a video of Lambert's audition for ''[[American Idol]]'' where he performed \"[[Bohemian Rhapsody]]\".<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.yahoo.com/music/bp/adam-lambert-reveals-discovered-queen-wayne-world-194736537.html |title=Adam Lambert Reveals He Discovered Queen Through \u2018Wayne\u2019s World\u2019 |work=Yahoo Music |author=Jon Wiederhorn |date=6 March 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011, Lambert joined Queen for a performance at the [[2011 MTV Europe Music Awards|MTV Europe Awards]] in [[Belfast]] where Queen received a Global Icon Award.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/adam-lambert-queen-mtv-emas-258086 |title=MTV EMAs: Adam Lambert Performs With Queen |author=Shirley Halperin |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=6 November 2011 }}</ref> It was then reported in December 2011 that Taylor and May had begun discussions with Lambert for him to front Queen in concert.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/42283/queen-adam-lambert-roger-taylor-talks-possible-live-dates |title=Queen + Adam Lambert? Roger Taylor Talks Possible Live Dates |work=Billboard |date=6 December 2011 }}</ref>  On 30 June 2012, Queen + Adam Lambert played their first full concert at [[Kiev]]'s [[Maidan Nezalezhnosti|Independence Square]] for a joint show with [[Elton John]] in aid of the [[Elena Pinchuk]] [[ANTIAIDS Foundation]].<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/adam-lambert-performs-bohemian-rhapsody-with-queen-in-kiev-20120701 |title=Adam Lambert Performs 'Bohemian Rhapsody' with Queen in Kiev|work= Rolling Stone |date=1 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Tours==\n\nAfter their first performance in Kiev in 2012, a [[Queen + Adam Lambert Tour 2012|Queen + Adam Lambert mini-tour]] followed with dates in [[Moscow]], [[Wroc\u0142aw]], and [[London]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.yahoo.com/music/bp/queen-adam-lambert-rock-london-queenbert-concert-094922439.html |title=Queen + Adam Lambert Rock London With \"Queenbert\" Concert |author=Lyndsey Parker |date=12 July 2012 |work= Yahoo! Music}}</ref> In September 2013, they appeared as a headliner at the [[iHeartRadio Music Festival]] in [[Las Vegas]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.yahoo.com/music/bp/they-are-the-champions--a-queen---adam-lambert-timeline-003807192.html |title=They Are the Champions: A Queen + Adam Lambert Timeline|author=Lyndsey Parker |date=14 June 2014 |work=Yahoo! Music Reality Rocks }}</ref> In March 2014, they announced a 19-date [[Queen + Adam Lambert Tour 2014\u20132015|Queen + Adam Lambert North American tour]] in the summer of 2014,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/queen-and-adam-lambert-to-reunite-for-summer-tour-20140306 |title=Queen and Adam Lambert to Reunite for Summer Tour|work= Rolling Stone |author = Jason Newman |date= 6 March 2014 }}</ref> which was then extended to 24 dates.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/queen-and-adam-lamberts-tour-opener-5-things-we-learned-20140620 | title=Queen and Adam Lambert's Tour Opener: 5 Things We Learned |author=Dan Hyman |work= Rolling Stone |date=20 June 2014 }}</ref>   In May 2014, tour dates in Australia were also announced,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/news/46350/queen-and-adam-lambert-announce-2014-australian-tour |title=Queen and Adam Lambert Announce 2014 Australian Tour|work=ARIA charts}}</ref> followed by New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/music/10274094/Queen-with-Lambert-announce-NZ-show |title=Queen with Lambert announce NZ show |date= 17 July 2014 |work=stuff.co.nz}}</ref> The band also performed in South Korea and Japan. The tour was then extended to 2015 with dates in Europe and the UK as well as South America.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/news/queen/80049 |title=Queen and Adam Lambert announce 2015 UK arena tour dates |work=NME |date=29 September 2014 |author=David Renshaw }}</ref>\n\n[[Queen + Adam Lambert 2016 Summer Festival Tour]] started on 20 May 2016 in [[Lisbon]], [[Portugal]] and ended on 30 September 2016 in [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]].\n\nOn 26 January 2017, a [[Queen + Adam Lambert Tour 2017\u20132018|26-date concert tour through North America]] was announced. The tour, which includes four dates in Canada, started on 23 June 2017 in Phoenix, Arizona and ended on 5 August 2017 in Houston, Texas.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.queenonline.com/en/news-archive/press-release-queen-adam-lambert-announce-25-date-north-american-tour/ |title=Press Release: Queen + Adam Lambert Announce 25 Date North American Tour |date= 26 January 2017 |publisher=QueenOnline.com}}</ref> In April 2017, it was announced that the tour would be expanded to include 26 dates in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.queenonline.com/en/news-archive/press-release-queen-adam-lambert-announce-uk-and-european-tour/|title=Press Release: Queen + Adam Lambert Announce UK and European Tour!|date=18 April 2017|publisher=QueenOnline.com|accessdate=18 April 2017}}</ref> Two months later, it was announced that the group would perform in New Zealand and Australia in February and March 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/tours/queen-and-adam-lambert-will-rock-you-down-under-early-next-year/news-story/380bf6210d57cf176de5370973a45284|title=Queen and Adam Lambert will rock you down under early next year|date=13 June 2017|publisher=news.com.au|accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> In February 2018, a second European leg was announced.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/entertainment/music/adam-lambert-and-queen-to-tour-germany-and-italy-in-2018/article/513902|title=Adam Lambert and Queen to tour Germany and Italy in 2018|date=3 February 2018|work=Digital Journal|access-date=3 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.queenonline.com/upcoming_shows|title=Upcoming Shows|publisher=QueenOnline.com|access-date=3 February 2018}}</ref> On 3 December 2018, Queen + Adam Lambert announced a North American tour taking place from July to August 2019, called [[The Rhapsody Tour]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ultimateclassicrock.com/queen-2019-rhapsody-tour/|title=Queen + Adam Lambert Announce 2019 North American Tour|first=Dave|last=Lifton|website=Ultimate Classic Rock}}</ref> On 7 April 2019 Queen + Adam Lambert announced they are bringing The Rhapsody Tour to Australia for 6 Stadium shows in February 2020 and on 8 April 2019 they announced 3 more shows in New Zealand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.queenonline.com/news/press-release-australian-dates-announced|title=Press Release: Australian Dates Announced!|publisher=QueenOnline.com|access-date=8 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.queenonline.com/news/press-release-new-zealand-shows-added|title=Press Release: New Zealand Shows Added!|publisher=QueenOnline.com|access-date=8 April 2019}}</ref> On 17 April 2019, four tour dates were announced for Japan in January 2020; Tokyo, Osaka and Aichi. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.queenonline.com/news/press-release-japanese-shows-added-to-rhapsody-tour-of-2020|title=QueenOnline.com - News|website=www.queenonline.com|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref> \n\n==Appearances==\nQueen + Adam Lambert have appeared on a number of television shows. On 30 November 2014 they performed \"[[Somebody to Love (Queen song)|Somebody to Love]]\" with the ''[[The X Factor (UK series 11)|X Factor]]'' contestants joining in the final chorus.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.fuse.tv/videos/2014/12/adam-lambert-queen-somebody-to-love-live-x-factor |title=  Watch Adam Lambert & Queen Slay \"Somebody to Love\" Live on 'X Factor' |author=Jeff Benjamin |date= 1 December 2014 |work=Fuse }}</ref>  The band performed two songs on the Christmas special  of the ''{{ill|Helene Fischer Show|de|Die Helene Fischer Show|vertical-align=sup}}'' on German television. One of them was \"[[I Want It All (Queen song)|I Want It All]]\" and the other was \"[[Who Wants to Live Forever]]\" which was a duet between Lambert and [[Helene Fischer]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blickamabend.ch/people/auftritte-von-take-that-queen-und-udo-juergens-das-erwartet-dich-in-der-helene-fischer-show-id3369399.html |title=Das erwartet dich in der \"Helene Fischer Show\" |work=Blick am Abend |author=Michel Imhof |date=25 December 2014 |access-date=27 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229024825/http://www.blickamabend.ch/people/auftritte-von-take-that-queen-und-udo-juergens-das-erwartet-dich-in-der-helene-fischer-show-id3369399.html |archive-date=29 December 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe band performed a special concert, [[Queen & Adam Lambert Rock Big Ben Live]], which was broadcast live on [[BBC One]] on New Year's Eve 2014 and into New Year's Day 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2014/queen-adam-lambert |title=Queen and Adam Lambert performed a New Year's Eve concert broadcast on BBC One called Queen + Adam Lambert Rock Big Ben Live |publisher=BBC |date= 1 December 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/dec/26/queen-freddie-mercury-present-throughout-show |title=Queen\u2019s Christmas message: \"We need a change of government\" |author=Kate Mossman|date= 26 December 2014 |work=The Guardian }}</ref> The concert was performed in the shadow of [[Big Ben]] in [[Central Hall Westminster]], and the show paused for the chimes of the Big Ben in the New Year countdown and the firework display in London.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a618924/new-years-eve-fireworks-watched-by-12-million-on-bbc-one.html |title =New Year's Eve Fireworks watched by 12 million on BBC One|author= Liam Martin |date= 1 January 2015 |work=Digital Spy }}</ref> In February 2017, the band appeared on ''[[The Late Late Show with James Corden]]'' where Corden and Lambert have a sing-off to determine who the better Queen frontman would be. In June 2017, they also made an appearance for ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'', where they performed multiple songs during a live concert sponsored by [[Mercedes-Benz]].\n\nQueen + Adam Lambert announced a 10-date residency at [[Park MGM|Park Theater]] in Las Vegas in September 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Queen + Adam Lambert To Rock Las Vegas|url=http://www.queenonline.com/news/press-release-queen-adam-lambert-to-rock-las-vegas|publisher=QueenOnline.com|accessdate=15 May 2018}}</ref> They also performed at the [[91st Academy Awards]] on 24 February 2019 to celebrate ''[[Bohemian Rhapsody (film)|Bohemian Rhapsody]].'' They then closed out Global Citizen Festival 2019 on 28 September.\n\nOn 16 February 2020 they appeared at [[Fire Fight Australia]], a 10 hour charity concert in [[Sydney]], [[Australia]] following the following the [[2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season]], where they performed the same set list that Queen performed at [[Live Aid]] in 1985.<ref>{{cite news|title=Queen reprises famous 1985 Live Aid set at Fire Fight Australia concert|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/music/fire-fight-relief-concert-raises-millions-for-bushfire-victims-20200216-p5419w.html|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|date=16 February 2020}}</ref> Afterwards, Brian May told fans on social media \"I don\u2019t think I\u2019ve felt quite like that since Live Aid.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-02-17/fire-fight-australia-queen-tops-five-memorable-moments/11971338|title=The Fire Fight Australia concert was full of memorable moments \u2014 here's five of the best|publisher=ABC News|date=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Brian May]] \u2013 guitar, backing and lead vocals (2011\u2013present)\n*[[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]] \u2013 drums, percussion, backing and lead vocals (2011\u2013present)\n*[[Adam Lambert]] \u2013 lead vocals (2011\u2013present)\n*[[Spike Edney]] \u2013 keyboards, backing vocals (2011\u2013present)\n*Neil Fairclough \u2013 bass guitar, backing vocals (2011\u2013present)\n*Tyler Warren - percussion, additional drums, backing vocals (2017\u2013present)\n\n===Former members===\n*[[Rufus Tiger Taylor]] \u2013 percussion, additional drums, backing vocals (2011\u201317)\n\n==Discography==\n*''Live in Japan'' (2016)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.queenonline.com Official Queen website]\n*{{dmoz|Arts/Music/Bands_and_Artists/Q/Queen|Queen}}\n*[http://www.adamlambert.net/ Official Adam Lambert website]\n\n{{Queen + Adam Lambert}}\n{{Queen}}\n{{Adam Lambert}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Queen plus Adam Lambert}}\n[[Category:Adam Lambert]]\n[[Category:Queen (band)]]\n[[Category:Supergroups (music)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Queen's and Adam Lambert collaboration, in which Adam provides lead vocals for the band}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Queen + Adam Lambert\n| alias            = {{flatlist|\n* Q+AL\n* QAL\n}}\n| image            = AdamLambert-Queen 7-1-14 SJ.jpg\n| caption          = Queen + Adam Lambert in concert in [[San Jose, California|San Jose]] in 2014, L\u2013R: [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]], [[Adam Lambert]], [[Brian May]]\n| image_size       = 250px\n| landscape        = yes\n| background       = group_or_band\n| origin           = {{plainlist|\n* United Kingdom\n* United States\n}}\n| genre            = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| years_active     = 2011\u2013present\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = [[Queen (band)|Queen]], [[Queen + Paul Rodgers]], [[Adam Lambert]]\n| current_members  = * [[Brian May]]\n* [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]]\n* [[Adam Lambert]]\n*[[Spike Edney]]\n*Neil Fairclough\n*Tyler Warren\n| past_members     = *[[Rufus Tiger Taylor]]\n}}\n'''Queen + Adam Lambert''' (sometimes referred to as '''Q+AL''' or '''QAL''') is a collaboration between the active members of the British band [[Queen (band)|Queen]] ([[Brian May]] and [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]]) and American vocalist [[Adam Lambert]]. As with all other Queen performances since 1997, longstanding bassist [[John Deacon]] has declined to participate in the project due to his retirement. This is the first long-term collaboration of Queen since the [[Queen + Paul Rodgers]] project ended in 2009. Like the previous project, it was made clear that Lambert would not be replacing Queen frontman [[Freddie Mercury]], but rather that he would be featured with the band's active members. The collaboration originated when May and Taylor appeared on ''[[American Idol (season 8)|American Idol]]'' in 2009 when Lambert was a contestant. They began performing occasionally in 2011, conducted a short [[Queen + Adam Lambert Tour 2012|European tour]] in 2012, and in 2014 announced a world tour, the [[Queen + Adam Lambert Tour 2014\u20132015]] with dates in North America, Australia, New Zealand, Asia, Europe and South America. In the summer of 2016, the group performed several dates as part of a festival tour in Europe and several dates in Asia. The next year, the group announced a second worldwide tour scheduled for 2017 and 2018 and later announced a short United Kingdom tour for 2020.\n\nJoining May, Taylor and Lambert are long-time Queen touring keyboardist [[Spike Edney]], bassist Neil Fairclough and percussionist Tyler Warren. Although there are currently no plans to release a studio album with this lineup, May and Taylor have stated that there is a possibility of the group recording original material.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/queen-recording-adam-lambert/|title=Queen Hint at Recording New Material with Adam Lambert|work=Ultimate Classic Rock}}</ref>\n\n==Origin==\nQueen and Lambert first performed together in 2009 when Queen members Brian May and Roger Taylor appeared as guests on the [[American Idol (season 8)|eighth season of ''American Idol'']] on which Lambert was a contestant. On the show, Lambert and the eventual winner [[Kris Allen]] performed \"[[We Are the Champions]]\" together with the band.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1611896/kris-allen-adam-lambert-tear-up-queens-we-are-the-champions/|title=Kris Allen, Adam Lambert Tear Up Queen\u2019s \u2018We Are The Champions\u2019|date=20 May 2009|first=Gil|last=Kaufman|work=MTV News|accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref> Soon after the finale, May indicated to ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' that he was considering Lambert as a frontman for Queen.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/exclusive-queens-brian-may-addresses-adam-lambert-rumors-20090522 |title= Exclusive: Queen's Brian May Addresses Adam Lambert Rumors |author=Brian Hiatt |date=22 May 2009 |work=Rolling Stone }}</ref> May later revealed that he became interested in Lambert as a replacement for [[Paul Rodgers]] after watching a video of Lambert's audition for ''[[American Idol]]'' where he performed \"[[Bohemian Rhapsody]]\".<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.yahoo.com/music/bp/adam-lambert-reveals-discovered-queen-wayne-world-194736537.html |title=Adam Lambert Reveals He Discovered Queen Through \u2018Wayne\u2019s World\u2019 |work=Yahoo Music |author=Jon Wiederhorn |date=6 March 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011, Lambert joined Queen for a performance at the [[2011 MTV Europe Music Awards|MTV Europe Awards]] in [[Belfast]] where Queen received a Global Icon Award.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/adam-lambert-queen-mtv-emas-258086 |title=MTV EMAs: Adam Lambert Performs With Queen |author=Shirley Halperin |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=6 November 2011 }}</ref> It was then reported in December 2011 that Taylor and May had begun discussions with Lambert for him to front Queen in concert.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/42283/queen-adam-lambert-roger-taylor-talks-possible-live-dates |title=Queen + Adam Lambert? Roger Taylor Talks Possible Live Dates |work=Billboard |date=6 December 2011 }}</ref>  On 30 June 2012, Queen + Adam Lambert played their first full concert at [[Kiev]]'s [[Maidan Nezalezhnosti|Independence Square]] for a joint show with [[Elton John]] in aid of the [[Elena Pinchuk]] [[ANTIAIDS Foundation]].<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/adam-lambert-performs-bohemian-rhapsody-with-queen-in-kiev-20120701 |title=Adam Lambert Performs 'Bohemian Rhapsody' with Queen in Kiev|work= Rolling Stone |date=1 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Tours==\n\nAfter their first performance in Kiev in 2012, a [[Queen + Adam Lambert Tour 2012|Queen + Adam Lambert mini-tour]] followed with dates in [[Moscow]], [[Wroc\u0142aw]], and [[London]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.yahoo.com/music/bp/queen-adam-lambert-rock-london-queenbert-concert-094922439.html |title=Queen + Adam Lambert Rock London With \"Queenbert\" Concert |author=Lyndsey Parker |date=12 July 2012 |work= Yahoo! Music}}</ref> In September 2013, they appeared as a headliner at the [[iHeartRadio Music Festival]] in [[Las Vegas]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.yahoo.com/music/bp/they-are-the-champions--a-queen---adam-lambert-timeline-003807192.html |title=They Are the Champions: A Queen + Adam Lambert Timeline|author=Lyndsey Parker |date=14 June 2014 |work=Yahoo! Music Reality Rocks }}</ref> In March 2014, they announced a 19-date [[Queen + Adam Lambert Tour 2014\u20132015|Queen + Adam Lambert North American tour]] in the summer of 2014,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/queen-and-adam-lambert-to-reunite-for-summer-tour-20140306 |title=Queen and Adam Lambert to Reunite for Summer Tour|work= Rolling Stone |author = Jason Newman |date= 6 March 2014 }}</ref> which was then extended to 24 dates.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/queen-and-adam-lamberts-tour-opener-5-things-we-learned-20140620 | title=Queen and Adam Lambert's Tour Opener: 5 Things We Learned |author=Dan Hyman |work= Rolling Stone |date=20 June 2014 }}</ref>   In May 2014, tour dates in Australia were also announced,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/news/46350/queen-and-adam-lambert-announce-2014-australian-tour |title=Queen and Adam Lambert Announce 2014 Australian Tour|work=ARIA charts}}</ref> followed by New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/music/10274094/Queen-with-Lambert-announce-NZ-show |title=Queen with Lambert announce NZ show |date= 17 July 2014 |work=stuff.co.nz}}</ref> The band also performed in South Korea and Japan. The tour was then extended to 2015 with dates in Europe and the UK as well as South America.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/news/queen/80049 |title=Queen and Adam Lambert announce 2015 UK arena tour dates |work=NME |date=29 September 2014 |author=David Renshaw }}</ref>\n\n[[Queen + Adam Lambert 2016 Summer Festival Tour]] started on 20 May 2016 in [[Lisbon]], [[Portugal]] and ended on 30 September 2016 in [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]].\n\nOn 26 January 2017, a [[Queen + Adam Lambert Tour 2017\u20132018|26-date concert tour through North America]] was announced. The tour, which includes four dates in Canada, started on 23 June 2017 in Phoenix, Arizona and ended on 5 August 2017 in Houston, Texas.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.queenonline.com/en/news-archive/press-release-queen-adam-lambert-announce-25-date-north-american-tour/ |title=Press Release: Queen + Adam Lambert Announce 25 Date North American Tour |date= 26 January 2017 |publisher=QueenOnline.com}}</ref> In April 2017, it was announced that the tour would be expanded to include 26 dates in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.queenonline.com/en/news-archive/press-release-queen-adam-lambert-announce-uk-and-european-tour/|title=Press Release: Queen + Adam Lambert Announce UK and European Tour!|date=18 April 2017|publisher=QueenOnline.com|accessdate=18 April 2017}}</ref> Two months later, it was announced that the group would perform in New Zealand and Australia in February and March 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/tours/queen-and-adam-lambert-will-rock-you-down-under-early-next-year/news-story/380bf6210d57cf176de5370973a45284|title=Queen and Adam Lambert will rock you down under early next year|date=13 June 2017|publisher=news.com.au|accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> In February 2018, a second European leg was announced.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/entertainment/music/adam-lambert-and-queen-to-tour-germany-and-italy-in-2018/article/513902|title=Adam Lambert and Queen to tour Germany and Italy in 2018|date=3 February 2018|work=Digital Journal|access-date=3 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.queenonline.com/upcoming_shows|title=Upcoming Shows|publisher=QueenOnline.com|access-date=3 February 2018}}</ref> On 3 December 2018, Queen + Adam Lambert announced a North American tour taking place from July to August 2019, called [[The Rhapsody Tour]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ultimateclassicrock.com/queen-2019-rhapsody-tour/|title=Queen + Adam Lambert Announce 2019 North American Tour|first=Dave|last=Lifton|website=Ultimate Classic Rock}}</ref> On 7 April 2019 Queen + Adam Lambert announced they are bringing The Rhapsody Tour to Australia for 6 Stadium shows in February 2020 and on 8 April 2019 they announced 3 more shows in New Zealand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.queenonline.com/news/press-release-australian-dates-announced|title=Press Release: Australian Dates Announced!|publisher=QueenOnline.com|access-date=8 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.queenonline.com/news/press-release-new-zealand-shows-added|title=Press Release: New Zealand Shows Added!|publisher=QueenOnline.com|access-date=8 April 2019}}</ref> On 17 April 2019, four tour dates were announced for Japan in January 2020; Tokyo, Osaka and Aichi. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.queenonline.com/news/press-release-japanese-shows-added-to-rhapsody-tour-of-2020|title=QueenOnline.com - News|website=www.queenonline.com|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref> \n\n==Appearances==\nQueen + Adam Lambert have appeared on a number of television shows. On 30 November 2014 they performed \"[[Somebody to Love (Queen song)|Somebody to Love]]\" with the ''[[The X Factor (UK series 11)|X Factor]]'' contestants joining in the final chorus.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.fuse.tv/videos/2014/12/adam-lambert-queen-somebody-to-love-live-x-factor |title=  Watch Adam Lambert & Queen Slay \"Somebody to Love\" Live on 'X Factor' |author=Jeff Benjamin |date= 1 December 2014 |work=Fuse }}</ref>  The band performed two songs on the Christmas special  of the ''{{ill|Helene Fischer Show|de|Die Helene Fischer Show|vertical-align=sup}}'' on German television. One of them was \"[[I Want It All (Queen song)|I Want It All]]\" and the other was \"[[Who Wants to Live Forever]]\" which was a duet between Lambert and [[Helene Fischer]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blickamabend.ch/people/auftritte-von-take-that-queen-und-udo-juergens-das-erwartet-dich-in-der-helene-fischer-show-id3369399.html |title=Das erwartet dich in der \"Helene Fischer Show\" |work=Blick am Abend |author=Michel Imhof |date=25 December 2014 |access-date=27 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229024825/http://www.blickamabend.ch/people/auftritte-von-take-that-queen-und-udo-juergens-das-erwartet-dich-in-der-helene-fischer-show-id3369399.html |archive-date=29 December 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe band performed a special concert, [[Queen & Adam Lambert Rock Big Ben Live]], which was broadcast live on [[BBC One]] on New Year's Eve 2014 and into New Year's Day 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2014/queen-adam-lambert |title=Queen and Adam Lambert performed a New Year's Eve concert broadcast on BBC One called Queen + Adam Lambert Rock Big Ben Live |publisher=BBC |date= 1 December 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/dec/26/queen-freddie-mercury-present-throughout-show |title=Queen\u2019s Christmas message: \"We need a change of government\" |author=Kate Mossman|date= 26 December 2014 |work=The Guardian }}</ref> The concert was performed in the shadow of [[Big Ben]] in [[Central Hall Westminster]], and the show paused for the chimes of the Big Ben in the New Year countdown and the firework display in London.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a618924/new-years-eve-fireworks-watched-by-12-million-on-bbc-one.html |title =New Year's Eve Fireworks watched by 12 million on BBC One|author= Liam Martin |date= 1 January 2015 |work=Digital Spy }}</ref> In February 2017, the band appeared on ''[[The Late Late Show with James Corden]]'' where Corden and Lambert have a sing-off to determine who the better Queen frontman would be. In June 2017, they also made an appearance for ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'', where they performed multiple songs during a live concert sponsored by [[Mercedes-Benz]].\n\nQueen + Adam Lambert announced a 10-date residency at [[Park MGM|Park Theater]] in Las Vegas in September 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Queen + Adam Lambert To Rock Las Vegas|url=http://www.queenonline.com/news/press-release-queen-adam-lambert-to-rock-las-vegas|publisher=QueenOnline.com|accessdate=15 May 2018}}</ref> They also performed at the [[91st Academy Awards]] on 24 February 2019 to celebrate ''[[Bohemian Rhapsody (film)|Bohemian Rhapsody]].'' They then closed out Global Citizen Festival 2019 on 28 September.\n\nOn 16 February 2020 they appeared at [[Fire Fight Australia]], a 10 hour charity concert in [[Sydney]], [[Australia]] following the following the [[2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season]], where they performed the same set list that Queen performed at [[Live Aid]] in 1985.<ref>{{cite news|title=Queen reprises famous 1985 Live Aid set at Fire Fight Australia concert|url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/music/fire-fight-relief-concert-raises-millions-for-bushfire-victims-20200216-p5419w.html|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|date=16 February 2020}}</ref> Afterwards, Brian May told fans on social media \"I don\u2019t think I\u2019ve felt quite like that since Live Aid.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-02-17/fire-fight-australia-queen-tops-five-memorable-moments/11971338|title=The Fire Fight Australia concert was full of memorable moments \u2014 here's five of the best|publisher=ABC News|date=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Brian May]] \u2013 guitar, backing and lead vocals (2011\u2013present)\n*[[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]] \u2013 drums, percussion, backing and lead vocals (2011\u2013present)\n*[[Adam Lambert]] \u2013 lead vocals (2011\u2013present)\n*[[Spike Edney]] \u2013 keyboards, backing vocals (2011\u2013present)\n*Neil Fairclough \u2013 bass guitar, backing vocals (2011\u2013present)\n*Tyler Warren - percussion, additional drums, backing vocals (2017\u2013present)\n\n===Former members===\n*[[Rufus Tiger Taylor]] \u2013 percussion, additional drums, backing vocals (2011\u201317)\n\n==Discography==\n*''Live in Japan'' (2016)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.queenonline.com Official Queen website]\n*{{dmoz|Arts/Music/Bands_and_Artists/Q/Queen|Queen}}\n*[http://www.adamlambert.net/ Official Adam Lambert website]\n\n{{Queen + Adam Lambert}}\n{{Queen}}\n{{Adam Lambert}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Queen plus Adam Lambert}}\n[[Category:Adam Lambert]]\n[[Category:Queen (band)]]\n[[Category:Supergroups (music)]]\n", "name_user": "2605:a000:1611:3fa:649f:136f:46b4:c9e3", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Jacob hargarve)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Queen_%2B_Adam_Lambert"}
